# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: build-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:build-systems/cmake] As a meta-build tool, CMake configures native build tools which in turn build the codebase.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake generates configuration files for other build tools based on CMake-specific configuration files.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The other tools are responsible for more directly building, using the generated files.
[src:build-systems/cmake] A single set of CMake-specific configuration files can be used to build a codebase using the native build tools of multiple platforms.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Notable native build tools supported by CMake include: Make, Qt Creator, Ninja, Android Studio, Xcode, and Visual Studio.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake is distributed as free and open-source software under a permissive BSD-3-Clause license.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Initial development began in 1999 at Kitware with funding from the United States National Library of Medicine as part of the Visible Human Project.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake was developed to support building the Insight Segmentation and Registration Toolkit (ITK) for multiple platforms.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Stated goals included addressing weaknesses while maintaining strengths of contemporary tools such as autoconf and libtool, and to align with state of the art build technology of the time: configure scripts and Make files for Unix platforms, and Visual Studio project files for Windows.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Both tools were working examples of a build tool that supported both Unix and Windows, but they suffered from a serious flaw: they required Windows developers to use the command line even though many prefer to use an integrated development environment (IDE) such as Visual Studio.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake was to provide similar cross-platform support but to better satisfy the preferences of the developers on each platform.
[src:build-systems/cmake] For various reasons, CMake developers chose to develop a scripting language for CMake instead of using Tcl – a popular language for building at the time.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Use of Tcl would have then added a dependency to the host machine which is counter to the goal of no dependencies other than a compiler.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Also, Tcl was not well supported on Windows and some Unix systems at the time of initial development.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Subsequent development and improvements were fueled by the incorporation of CMake into developers’ own systems, including the VXL Project, the CABLE features added by Brad King, and GE Corporate R&D for support of DART (which is depracated since 3.7.).
[src:build-systems/cmake] Additional features were created when VTK transitioned to CMake for its build environment and for supporting ParaView.
[src:build-systems/cmake] It has been described as the beginning of "Modern CMake".
[src:build-systems/cmake] Experts now advise to avoid variables in favor of *targets* and *properties*.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The commands `add_compile_options`, `include_directories`, `link_directories`, `link_libraries` that were at the core of CMake 2 should now be replaced by target-specific commands.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake developer Brad King stated that "the 'C' in CMake stands for 'cross-platform'".
[src:build-systems/cmake] By default, CMake automatically determines default generator for the host environment it runs on.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Command line option `-G` can be used to specify alternative generator.
[src:build-systems/cmake] `-G Unix Makefiles` forces CMake to create build scripts for make.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake does not support custom generators without modifying the CMake implementation.
[src:build-systems/cmake] None-the-less, the CMake source code could be modified to include a custom generator.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake supports building executables, libraries (e.g.
[src:build-systems/cmake] `libxyz`, `xyz.dll` etc.), object file libraries and pseudo-targets (including aliases).
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake can produce object files that can be linked against by executable binaries/libraries, avoiding dynamic (run-time) linking and using static (compile-time) linking instead.
[src:build-systems/cmake] This enables flexibility in configuration of various optimizations.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Target generation can be configured via target properties.
[src:build-systems/cmake] With older versions, this was done via `CMAKE_`-prefixed global variables, but this approach is deprecated.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake configuration files can be structured according the hierarchical structure of the source code; the source tree.
[src:build-systems/cmake] A `CMakeLists.txt` in a root source directory serves as the root of the configuration.
[src:build-systems/cmake] It may include sub-directories which each contain a `CMakeLists.txt`.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Repeating this, results in a hierarchical structure of configuration that follows the structure of the source code.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake can store generated files (both by CMake and the native build tools) in a directory tree that is separate from the source tree.
[src:build-systems/cmake] This enables multiple builds from the same source tree since each has non-overlapping file system space.
[src:build-systems/cmake] This may be leveraged to build different or even incompatible configurations such as for different platforms.
[src:build-systems/cmake] This also simplifies file management by allowing removing generated files by deleting a single directory tree instead of removing multiple files and directories throughout the source tree.
[src:build-systems/cmake] This tends to prevent accidentally deleting source files or accidentally adding generated files to source control.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake ensures that downstream components are re-built when its sources are changed or built.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake can locate system-wide and user-specified executables, files, and libraries.
[src:build-systems/cmake] These locations are stored in a cache, which can then be tailored before generating the target build files.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The cache can be edited with a graphical editor, which is shipped with CMake.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Complicated directory hierarchies and applications that rely on several libraries are well supported by CMake.
[src:build-systems/cmake] For instance, CMake is able to accommodate a project that has multiple toolkits, or libraries that each have multiple directories.
[src:build-systems/cmake] In addition, CMake can work with projects that require executables to be created before generating code to be compiled for the final application.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Its open-source, extensible design allows CMake to be adapted as necessary for specific projects.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake allows specification of features that the compiler is required to support in order to get the target program or library compiled.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake supports many compilers, including: Apple Clang, Clang, GNU GCC, MSVC, Oracle Developer Studio, and Intel C++ Compiler.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake can produce packages that can be consumed both by end-user and third-party cmake-based project.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Via CPack, built files may be packed into an archive file for a target system's package manager (e.g. dpkg) or installer supported by the target platform.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake provides functions for pulling packages from a remote server that can be used as part of the build process or link previously installed cmake packages.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Cmake may be run by using a ncurses program like `ccmake` that can be used to configure projects via command-line interface.
[src:build-systems/cmake] It is possible to generate precompiled headers via CMake since version 3.6.
[src:build-systems/cmake] As of version 3.28, CMake can also compile modules.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Experimental support for header units also exists.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake supports extracting values into variables from JSON-data strings (since version 3.19).
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake includes an interpreter for a relatively simple, custom, imperative scripting language that supports variables, string manipulation, arrays, function and macro declaration, and module inclusion (importing).
[src:build-systems/cmake] The interpreter reads CMake language commands from files named `CMakeLists.txt` which specify source files and build preferences.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake uses this information to generate native tool configuration files.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Additionally, files with suffix `.cmake` can be used for storing additional script.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Arguments are whitespace-separated and can include keywords to separate groups of arguments.
[src:build-systems/cmake] For instance, in the following command, the keyword `COMPILE_FLAGS` delimits a list of source files from compiler flags.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The CMake scripting language is implemented via Yacc and Lex generators.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The executable programs CMake, CPack, and CTest are written in C++.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Much of CMake's functionality is implemented in modules written in the CMake language.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake documentation (since release 3.0) uses reStructuredText markup.
[src:build-systems/cmake] HTML pages and man pages are generated by the Sphinx documentation generator.
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake ships with numerous `.cmake` script files and development tools that facilitate tasks such as finding dependencies (both built-in and external, e.g.
[src:build-systems/cmake] `FindXYZ` modules), testing the toolchain environment and executables, packaging releases (CPack), and managing dependencies on external projects (`ExternalProject` module).
[src:build-systems/cmake] CMake has been very widely adopted among commercial, open source, and academic software projects.
[src:build-systems/cmake] A few notable users include Android NDK, Netflix, Inria, MySQL, Boost (C++ libraries), KeePassXC, KDE, KiCAD, FreeCAD, Webkit, Blender, Biicode, ReactOS, Apache Qpid, the ATLAS experiment, and Second Life.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Building via CMake has two major stages.
[src:build-systems/cmake] First, native build tool configuration files are generated from CMake configuration files – written in the CMake scripting language.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The command line syntax is `cmake <dir>` where <dir> is a directory that contains a `CMakeLists.txt` file.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Then, the native build tools are invoked either via CMake (`cmake --build <dir>`) or directly via the native tool's interface.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The native build tools use the generated files.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The following demonstrates configuring CMake to build a hello world program written in C++, and using CMake to build the program.
[src:build-systems/cmake] To build via CMake, first cd to the directory containing the two files above.
[src:build-systems/cmake] All generated files will be under the directory *out* as specified via `-B out`.
[src:build-systems/cmake] The program is then available for running.
[src:build-systems/cmake] Via Bash, the command is like `./out/hello`.
[src:build-systems/cmake] On Windows, the output file ends with `.exe`.
[src:build-systems/cmake] This example demonstrates configuring the preprocessor include path.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In software development, **Make** is a command-line interface software tool that performs actions ordered by configured dependencies as defined in a configuration file called a *makefile*.
[src:build-systems/make-software] It is commonly used for build automation to build executable code (such as a program or library) from source code.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make is also not limited to building and can perform any operation available via the operating system shell.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make is widely used, especially in Unix and Unix-like operating systems, even though many competing technologies and tools are available, including similar tools that perform actions based on dependencies, some compilers and interactively via an integrated development environment.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In addition to referring to the original Unix tool, Make is also a technology since multiple tools have been implemented with roughly the same functionality – including similar makefile syntax and semantics.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Stuart Feldman created Make while at Bell Labs.
[src:build-systems/make-software] An early version was completed in April 1976.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Feldman received the 2003 ACM Software System Award for authoring Make.
[src:build-systems/make-software] — Stuart Feldman, *The Art of Unix Programming*, Eric S.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Before Make, building on Unix mostly consisted of shell scripts written for each program's codebase.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make's dependency ordering and out-of-date checking makes the build process more robust and more efficient.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The makefile allowed for better organization of build logic and often fewer build files.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make is widely used in part due to its early inclusion in Unix, starting with PWB/UNIX 1.0, which featured a variety of software development tools.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make has been implemented numerous times, generally using the same makefile format and providing the same features, but some providing enhancements from the original.
[src:build-systems/make-software] POSIX includes standardization of the basic features and operation of the Make utility, and is implemented with varying degrees of compatibility with Unix-based versions of Make.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In general, simple makefiles may be used between various versions of Make with reasonable success.
[src:build-systems/make-software] GNU Make, Makepp and some versions of BSD Make default to looking first for files named "GNUmakefile", "Makeppfile" and "BSDmakefile" respectively, which allows one to put makefiles which use implementation-defined behavior in separate locations.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In general, based on a makefile, Make updates target files from source files if any source file has a newer timestamp than the target file or the target file does not exist.
[src:build-systems/make-software] For example, this could include compiling C files (`*.c`) into object files, then linking the object files into an executable program.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Or this could include compiling TypeScript files (`*.ts`) to JavaScript for use in a browser.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Other examples include: convert a source image file to another format, copy a file to a content management system, and send e-mail about build status.
[src:build-systems/make-software] A makefile defines targets where each is either a file to generate or is a user-defined concept, called a *phony* target.
[src:build-systems/make-software] If no target is specified, Make updates the first target in the makefile which is often a phony target to perform the most commonly used action.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make skips build actions if the target file timestamp is after that of the source files.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Also, if a source file's timestamp is in the future, make repeatedly triggers unnecessary actions, causing longer build time.
[src:build-systems/make-software] When Make starts, it uses the makefile specified on the command-line or if not specified, then uses the one found by via specific search rules.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Generally, Make defaults to using the file in the working directory named Makefile.
[src:build-systems/make-software] GNU Make searches for the first file matching: GNUmakefile, makefile, or Makefile.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make processes the options of the command-line based on the loaded makefile.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The **makefile** language is partially declarative programming where end conditions are described but the order in which actions are to be taken is not.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Each rule begins with a *dependency line* which consists of the rule's target name followed by a colon (:), and optionally a list of targets (also known as prerequisites) on which the rule's target depends.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Usually a rule has a single target, rather than multiple.
[src:build-systems/make-software] A dependency line may be followed by a recipe: a series of TAB indented command lines that define how to generate the target from the components (i.e. source files).
[src:build-systems/make-software] If any prerequisite has a more recent timestamp than the target file or the target does not exist as a file, the recipe is performed.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Each command line must begin with a tab character.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Even though a space is also whitespace, Make requires tab.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Since this often leads to confusion and mistakes, this aspect of makefile syntax is subject to criticism.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Raymond describes it as "one of the worst design botches in the history of Unix" and *The Unix-Haters Handbook* said "using tabs as part of the syntax is like one of those pungee [sic] stick traps in *The Green Berets*".
[src:build-systems/make-software] Each command is executed in a separate shell.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Since operating systems use different shells, this can lead to unportable makefiles.
[src:build-systems/make-software] For example, GNU Make (all POSIX Makes) executes commands with /bin/sh by default, where Unix commands like cp are normally used.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In contrast, Microsoft's *nmake* executes commands with cmd.exe where batch commands like copy are available but not necessarily cp.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The following example rule is evaluated when Make updates target file.txt via `make file.txt`.
[src:build-systems/make-software] If file.html is newer than file.txt or file.txt does not exist, then the command is run to generate file.txt from file.html.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Ignoring errors and silencing echo can alternatively be obtained via the special targets `.IGNORE` and `.SILENT`.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Microsoft's NMAKE has predefined rules that can be omitted from these makefiles, e.g.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Macros are usually referred to as *variables* when they hold simple string definitions, like `CC=clang`.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Macros in makefiles may be overridden in the command-line arguments passed to the Make utility.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Environment variables are also available as macros.
[src:build-systems/make-software] For example, the macro `CC` is frequently used in makefiles to refer to the location of a C compiler.
[src:build-systems/make-software] If used consistently throughout the makefile, then the compiler used can be changed by changing the value of the macro rather than changing each rule command that invokes the compiler.
[src:build-systems/make-software] A macro value can consist of other macro values.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The value of macro is expanded on each use lazily.
[src:build-systems/make-software] A macro is used by expanding either via $*NAME* or $(*NAME*).
[src:build-systems/make-software] The latter is safer since omitting the parentheses leads to Make interpreting the next letter after the `$` as the entire variable name.
[src:build-systems/make-software] An equivalent form uses curly braces rather than parentheses, i.e.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Macros can be composed of shell commands by using the command substitution operator `!=`.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Makefiles can access predefined *internal macros*, with `?` and `@` being common.
[src:build-systems/make-software] A common syntax when defining macros, which works on BSD and GNU Make, is to use +=, ?=, and != instead of the equal sign (=).
[src:build-systems/make-software] Suffix rules have "targets" with names in the form `.FROM.TO` and are used to launch actions based on file extension.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In the command lines of suffix rules, POSIX specifies that the internal macro `$<` refers to the first prerequisite and `$@` refers to the target.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Suffix rules cannot have any prerequisites of their own.
[src:build-systems/make-software] If they have any, they are treated as normal files with unusual names, not as suffix rules.
[src:build-systems/make-software] GNU Make supports suffix rules for compatibility with old makefiles but otherwise encourages usage of *pattern rules*.
[src:build-systems/make-software] A pattern rule looks like an ordinary rule, except that its target contains exactly one `%` character within the string.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The target is considered a pattern for matching file names: the `%` can match any substring of zero or more characters, while other characters match only themselves.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The prerequisites likewise use `%` to show how their names relate to the target name.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Single-line comments are started with the hash symbol (#).
[src:build-systems/make-software] A directive specifies special behavior such as including another makefile.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Line continuation is indicated with a backslash `\` character at the end of a line.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The following commands are in the context of the makefile that follows.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Below is a simple makefile that by default (the "all" rule is listed first) compiles a source file called "helloworld.c" using the system's C compiler and also provides a "clean" target to remove the generated files if the user desires to start over.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The `$@` and `$<` are two of the so-called internal macros (also known as automatic variables) and stand for the target name and "implicit" source, respectively.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In the example below, `$^` expands to a space delimited list of the prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/make-software] There are a number of other internal macros.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Many systems come with predefined Make rules and macros to specify common tasks such as compilation based on file suffix.
[src:build-systems/make-software] This lets users omit the actual (often unportable) instructions of how to generate the target from the source(s).
[src:build-systems/make-software] That "helloworld.o" depends on "helloworld.c" is now automatically handled by Make.
[src:build-systems/make-software] In such a simple example as the one illustrated here this hardly matters, but the real power of suffix rules becomes evident when the number of source files in a software project starts to grow.
[src:build-systems/make-software] One only has to write a rule for the linking step and declare the object files as prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Make will then implicitly determine how to make all the object files and look for changes in all the source files.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Simple suffix rules work well as long as the source files do not depend on each other and on other files such as header files.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Another route to simplify the build process is to use so-called pattern matching rules that can be combined with compiler-assisted dependency generation.
[src:build-systems/make-software] As a final example requiring the gcc compiler and GNU Make, here is a generic makefile that compiles all C files in a folder to the corresponding object files and then links them to the final executable.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Before compilation takes place, dependencies are gathered in makefile-friendly format into a hidden file ".depend" that is then included to the makefile.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Portable programs ought to avoid constructs used below.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Makefile consist of dependencies and a forgotten or an extra one may not be immediately obvious to the user and may result in subtle bugs in the generated software that are hard to catch.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Various approaches may be used to avoid this problem and keep dependencies in source and makefiles in sync.
[src:build-systems/make-software] One approach is using the compiler to keep track of dependencies changes.
[src:build-systems/make-software] GCC can statically analyze the source code and produce rules for the given file automatically by using the `-MM` switch.
[src:build-systems/make-software] The other approach would be makefiles or third-party tools that would generate makefiles with dependencies (e.g.
[src:build-systems/make-software] Automake toolchain by the GNU Project, can do so automatically).
[src:build-systems/make-software] Another approach is to use meta-build tools like CMake, Meson etc.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This file documents the GNU `make` utility, which determines automatically which pieces of a large program need to be recompiled, and issues the commands to recompile them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This is Edition 0.77, last updated 26 February 2023, of *The GNU Make Manual*, for GNU `make` version 4.4.1.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The `make` utility automatically determines which pieces of a large program need to be recompiled, and issues commands to recompile them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This manual describes GNU `make`, which was implemented by Richard Stallman and Roland McGrath.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Development since Version 3.76 has been handled by Paul D.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Our examples show C programs, since they are most common, but you can use `make` with any programming language whose compiler can be run with a shell command.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Indeed, `make` is not limited to programs.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] You can use it to describe any task where some files must be updated automatically from others whenever the others change.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] To prepare to use `make`, you must write a file called the *makefile* that describes the relationships among files in your program and provides commands for updating each file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In a program, typically, the executable file is updated from object files, which are in turn made by compiling source files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] suffices to perform all necessary recompilations.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The `make` program uses the makefile data base and the last-modification times of the files to decide which of the files need to be updated.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] For each of those files, it issues the recipes recorded in the data base.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] You can provide command line arguments to `make` to control which files should be recompiled, or how.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If you are new to `make`, or are looking for a general introduction, read the first few sections of each chapter, skipping the later sections.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In each chapter, the first few sections contain introductory or general information and the later sections contain specialized or technical information.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The exception is the second chapter, An Introduction to Makefiles, all of which is introductory.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If you are familiar with other `make` programs, see Features of GNU `make`, which lists the enhancements GNU `make` has, and Incompatibilities and Missing Features, which explains the few things GNU `make` lacks that others have.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] For a quick summary, see Summary of Options, Quick Reference, and Special Built-in Target Names.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If you have problems with GNU `make` or think you’ve found a bug, please report it to the developers; we cannot promise to do anything but we might well want to fix it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Before reporting a bug, make sure you’ve actually found a real bug.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Carefully reread the documentation and see if it really says you can do what you’re trying to do.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If it’s not clear whether you should be able to do something or not, report that too; it’s a bug in the documentation!
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Before reporting a bug or trying to fix it yourself, try to isolate it to the smallest possible makefile that reproduces the problem.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Then send us the makefile and the exact results `make` gave you, including any error or warning messages.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Please don’t paraphrase these messages: it’s best to cut and paste them into your report.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] When generating this small makefile, be sure to not use any non-free or unusual tools in your recipes: you can almost always emulate what such a tool would do with simple shell commands.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Finally, be sure to explain what you expected to occur; this will help us decide whether the problem was really in the documentation.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Once you have a precise problem you can report it in one of two ways.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In addition to the information above, please be careful to include the version number of `make` you are using.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] You can get this information with the command ‘make --version’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Be sure also to include the type of machine and operating system you are using.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] One way to obtain this information is by looking at the final lines of output from the command ‘make --help’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If you have a code change you’d like to submit, see the README file section “Submitting Patches” for information.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] You need a file called a *makefile* to tell `make` what to do.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Most often, the makefile tells `make` how to compile and link a program.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In this chapter, we will discuss a simple makefile that describes how to compile and link a text editor which consists of eight C source files and three header files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The makefile can also tell `make` how to run miscellaneous commands when explicitly asked (for example, to remove certain files as a clean-up operation).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] To see a more complex example of a makefile, see Complex Makefile Example.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] When `make` recompiles the editor, each changed C source file must be recompiled.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If a header file has changed, each C source file that includes the header file must be recompiled to be safe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Each compilation produces an object file corresponding to the source file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Finally, if any source file has been recompiled, all the object files, whether newly made or saved from previous compilations, must be linked together to produce the new executable editor.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A *target* is usually the name of a file that is generated by a program; examples of targets are executable or object files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A target can also be the name of an action to carry out, such as ‘clean’ (see Phony Targets).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A *prerequisite* is a file that is used as input to create the target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A target often depends on several files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A *recipe* is an action that `make` carries out.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A recipe may have more than one command, either on the same line or each on its own line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] **Please note:** you need to put a tab character at the beginning of every recipe line!
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This is an obscurity that catches the unwary.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If you prefer to prefix your recipes with a character other than tab, you can set the `.RECIPEPREFIX` variable to an alternate character (see Other Special Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Usually a recipe is in a rule with prerequisites and serves to create a target file if any of the prerequisites change.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] However, the rule that specifies a recipe for the target need not have prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] For example, the rule containing the delete command associated with the target ‘clean’ does not have prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A *rule*, then, explains how and when to remake certain files which are the targets of the particular rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] `make` carries out the recipe on the prerequisites to create or update the target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A rule can also explain how and when to carry out an action.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A makefile may contain other text besides rules, but a simple makefile need only contain rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Rules may look somewhat more complicated than shown in this template, but all fit the pattern more or less.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Here is a straightforward makefile that describes the way an executable file called `edit` depends on eight object files which, in turn, depend on eight C source and three header files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In this example, all the C files include defs.h, but only those defining editing commands include command.h, and only low level files that change the editor buffer include buffer.h.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] We split each long line into two lines using backslash/newline; this is like using one long line, but is easier to read.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In the example makefile, the targets include the executable file ‘edit’, and the object files ‘main.o’ and ‘kbd.o’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The prerequisites are files such as ‘main.c’ and ‘defs.h’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In fact, each ‘.o’ file is both a target and a prerequisite.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Recipes include ‘cc -c main.c’ and ‘cc -c kbd.c’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] When a target is a file, it needs to be recompiled or relinked if any of its prerequisites change.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In addition, any prerequisites that are themselves automatically generated should be updated first.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In this example, edit depends on each of the eight object files; the object file main.o depends on the source file main.c and on the header file defs.h.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A recipe may follow each line that contains a target and prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] These recipes say how to update the target file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A tab character (or whatever character is specified by the `.RECIPEPREFIX` variable; see Other Special Variables) must come at the beginning of every line in the recipe to distinguish recipes from other lines in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] (Bear in mind that `make` does not know anything about how the recipes work.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] It is up to you to supply recipes that will update the target file properly.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The target ‘clean’ is not a file, but merely the name of an action.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Since you normally do not want to carry out the actions in this rule, ‘clean’ is not a prerequisite of any other rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Consequently, `make` never does anything with it unless you tell it specifically.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Note that this rule not only is not a prerequisite, it also does not have any prerequisites, so the only purpose of the rule is to run the specified recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Targets that do not refer to files but are just actions are called *phony targets*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] See Phony Targets, for information about this kind of target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] See Errors in Recipes, to see how to cause `make` to ignore errors from `rm` or any other command.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] By default, `make` starts with the first target (not targets whose names start with ‘.’ unless they also contain one or more ‘/’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] (*Goals* are the targets that `make` strives ultimately to update.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] You can override this behavior using the command line (see Arguments to Specify the Goals) or with the `.DEFAULT_GOAL` special variable (see Other Special Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In the simple example of the previous section, the default goal is to update the executable program edit; therefore, we put that rule first.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] `make` reads the makefile in the current directory and begins by processing the first rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In the example, this rule is for relinking edit; but before `make` can fully process this rule, it must process the rules for the files that edit depends on, which in this case are the object files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Each of these files is processed according to its own rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] These rules say to update each ‘.o’ file by compiling its source file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The recompilation must be done if the source file, or any of the header files named as prerequisites, is more recent than the object file, or if the object file does not exist.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] The other rules are processed because their targets appear as prerequisites of the goal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If some other rule is not depended on by the goal (or anything it depends on, etc.), that rule is not processed, unless you tell `make` to do so (with a command such as `make clean`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Before recompiling an object file, `make` considers updating its prerequisites, the source file and header files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This makefile does not specify anything to be done for them—the ‘.c’ and ‘.h’ files are not the targets of any rules—so `make` does nothing for these files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] But `make` would update automatically generated C programs, such as those made by Bison or Yacc, by their own rules at this time.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] After recompiling whichever object files need it, `make` decides whether to relink edit.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This must be done if the file edit does not exist, or if any of the object files are newer than it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If an object file was just recompiled, it is now newer than edit, so edit is relinked.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Thus, if we change the file insert.c and run `make`, `make` will compile that file to update insert.o, and then link edit.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] If we change the file command.h and run `make`, `make` will recompile the object files kbd.o, command.o and files.o and then link the file edit.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Such duplication is error-prone; if a new object file is added to the system, we might add it to one list and forget the other.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] We can eliminate the risk and simplify the makefile by using a variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] *Variables* allow a text string to be defined once and substituted in multiple places later (see How to Use Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] It is standard practice for every makefile to have a variable named `objects`, `OBJECTS`, `objs`, `OBJS`, `obj`, or `OBJ` which is a list of all object file names.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Then, each place we want to put a list of the object file names, we can substitute the variable’s value by writing ‘$(objects)’ (see How to Use Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] It is not necessary to spell out the recipes for compiling the individual C source files, because `make` can figure them out: it has an *implicit rule* for updating a ‘.o’ file from a correspondingly named ‘.c’ file using a ‘cc -c’ command.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] For example, it will use the recipe ‘cc -c main.c -o main.o’ to compile main.c into main.o.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] We can therefore omit the recipes from the rules for the object files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] When a ‘.c’ file is used automatically in this way, it is also automatically added to the list of prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] We can therefore omit the ‘.c’ files from the prerequisites, provided we omit the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This is how we would write the makefile in actual practice.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] (The complications associated with ‘clean’ are described elsewhere.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Because implicit rules are so convenient, they are important.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] When the objects of a makefile are created only by implicit rules, an alternative style of makefile is possible.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In this style of makefile, you group entries by their prerequisites instead of by their targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Here defs.h is given as a prerequisite of all the object files; command.h and buffer.h are prerequisites of the specific object files listed for them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Whether this is better is a matter of taste: it is more compact, but some people dislike it because they find it clearer to put all the information about each target in one place.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Compiling a program is not the only thing you might want to write rules for.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Makefiles commonly tell how to do a few other things besides compiling a program: for example, how to delete all the object files and executables so that the directory is ‘clean’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In practice, we might want to write the rule in a somewhat more complicated manner to handle unanticipated situations.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] This prevents `make` from getting confused by an actual file called clean and causes it to continue in spite of errors from `rm`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] A rule such as this should not be placed at the beginning of the makefile, because we do not want it to run by default!
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Thus, in the example makefile, we want the rule for `edit`, which recompiles the editor, to remain the default goal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] Since `clean` is not a prerequisite of `edit`, this rule will not run at all if we give the command ‘make’ with no arguments.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p01] In order to make the rule run, we have to type ‘make clean’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The information that tells `make` how to recompile a system comes from reading a data base called the *makefile*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] By default, when `make` looks for the makefile, it tries the following names, in order: GNUmakefile, makefile and Makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Normally you should call your makefile either makefile or Makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] (We recommend Makefile because it appears prominently near the beginning of a directory listing, right near other important files such as README.) The first name checked, GNUmakefile, is not recommended for most makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] You should use this name if you have a makefile that is specific to GNU `make`, and will not be understood by other versions of `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Other `make` programs look for makefile and Makefile, but not GNUmakefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If `make` finds none of these names, it does not use any makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Then you must specify a goal with a command argument, and `make` will attempt to figure out how to remake it using only its built-in implicit rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you want to use a nonstandard name for your makefile, you can specify the makefile name with the ‘-f’ or ‘--file’ option.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The arguments ‘-f *name*’ or ‘--file=*name*’ tell `make` to read the file *name* as the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you use more than one ‘-f’ or ‘--file’ option, you can specify several makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] All the makefiles are effectively concatenated in the order specified.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The default makefile names GNUmakefile, makefile and Makefile are not checked automatically if you specify ‘-f’ or ‘--file’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The `include` directive tells `make` to suspend reading the current makefile and read one or more other makefiles before continuing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Extra spaces are allowed and ignored at the beginning of the line, but the first character must not be a tab (or the value of `.RECIPEPREFIX`)—if the line begins with a tab, it will be considered a recipe line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Whitespace is required between `include` and the file names, and between file names; extra whitespace is ignored there and at the end of the directive.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] A comment starting with ‘#’ is allowed at the end of the line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If the file names contain any variable or function references, they are expanded.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] When `make` processes an `include` directive, it suspends reading of the containing makefile and reads from each listed file in turn.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] When that is finished, `make` resumes reading the makefile in which the directive appears.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] One occasion for using `include` directives is when several programs, handled by individual makefiles in various directories, need to use a common set of variable definitions (see Setting Variables) or pattern rules (see Defining and Redefining Pattern Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Another such occasion is when you want to generate prerequisites from source files automatically; the prerequisites can be put in a file that is included by the main makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This practice is generally cleaner than that of somehow appending the prerequisites to the end of the main makefile as has been traditionally done with other versions of `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] See Generating Prerequisites Automatically.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If the specified name does not start with a slash (or a drive letter and colon when GNU Make is compiled with MS-DOS / MS-Windows path support), and the file is not found in the current directory, several other directories are searched.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] First, any directories you have specified with the ‘-I’ or ‘--include-dir’ options are searched (see Summary of Options).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Then the following directories (if they exist) are searched, in this order: *prefix*/include (normally /usr/local/include 1) /usr/gnu/include, /usr/local/include, /usr/include.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The `.INCLUDE_DIRS` variable will contain the current list of directories that make will search for included files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] You can avoid searching in these default directories by adding the command line option `-I` with the special value `-` (e.g., `-I-`) to the command line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This will cause `make` to forget any already-set include directories, including the default directories.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If an included makefile cannot be found in any of these directories it is not an immediately fatal error; processing of the makefile containing the `include` continues.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Once it has finished reading makefiles, `make` will try to remake any that are out of date or don’t exist.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Only after it has failed to find a rule to remake the makefile, or it found a rule but the recipe failed, will `make` diagnose the missing makefile as a fatal error.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This acts like `include` in every way except that there is no error (not even a warning) if any of the *filenames* (or any prerequisites of any of the *filenames*) do not exist or cannot be remade.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] For compatibility with some other `make` implementations, `sinclude` is another name for `-include`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If the environment variable `MAKEFILES` is defined, `make` considers its value as a list of names (separated by whitespace) of additional makefiles to be read before the others.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This works much like the `include` directive: various directories are searched for those files (see Including Other Makefiles).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In addition, the default goal is never taken from one of these makefiles (or any makefile included by them) and it is not an error if the files listed in `MAKEFILES` are not found.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The main use of `MAKEFILES` is in communication between recursive invocations of `make` (see Recursive Use of `make`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] It usually is not desirable to set the environment variable before a top-level invocation of `make`, because it is usually better not to mess with a makefile from outside.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] However, if you are running `make` without a specific makefile, a makefile in `MAKEFILES` can do useful things to help the built-in implicit rules work better, such as defining search paths (see Searching Directories for Prerequisites).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Some users are tempted to set `MAKEFILES` in the environment automatically on login, and program makefiles to expect this to be done.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This is a very bad idea, because such makefiles will fail to work if run by anyone else.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] It is much better to write explicit `include` directives in the makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Sometimes makefiles can be remade from other files, such as RCS or SCCS files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If a makefile can be remade from other files, you probably want `make` to get an up-to-date version of the makefile to read in.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] To this end, after reading in all makefiles `make` will consider each as a goal target, in the order in which they were processed, and attempt to update it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If parallel builds (see Parallel Execution) are enabled then makefiles will be rebuilt in parallel as well.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If a makefile has a rule which says how to update it (found either in that very makefile or in another one) or if an implicit rule applies to it (see Using Implicit Rules), it will be updated if necessary.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] After all makefiles have been checked, if any have actually been changed, `make` starts with a clean slate and reads all the makefiles over again.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] (It will also attempt to update each of them over again, but normally this will not change them again, since they are already up to date.) Each restart will cause the special variable `MAKE_RESTARTS` to be updated (see Other Special Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you know that one or more of your makefiles cannot be remade and you want to keep `make` from performing an implicit rule search on them, perhaps for efficiency reasons, you can use any normal method of preventing implicit rule look-up to do so.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] For example, you can write an explicit rule with the makefile as the target, and an empty recipe (see Using Empty Recipes).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If the makefiles specify a double-colon rule to remake a file with a recipe but no prerequisites, that file will always be remade (see Double-Colon Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In the case of makefiles, a makefile that has a double-colon rule with a recipe but no prerequisites will be remade every time `make` is run, and then again after `make` starts over and reads the makefiles in again.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This would cause an infinite loop: `make` would constantly remake the makefile and restart, and never do anything else.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] So, to avoid this, `make` will **not** attempt to remake makefiles which are specified as targets of a double-colon rule with a recipe but no prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Phony targets (see Phony Targets) have the same effect: they are never considered up-to-date and so an included file marked as phony would cause `make` to restart continuously.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] To avoid this `make` will not attempt to remake makefiles which are marked phony.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you do not specify any makefiles to be read with ‘-f’ or ‘--file’ options, `make` will try the default makefile names; see What Name to Give Your Makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Unlike makefiles explicitly requested with ‘-f’ or ‘--file’ options, `make` is not certain that these makefiles should exist.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] However, if a default makefile does not exist but can be created by running `make` rules, you probably want the rules to be run so that the makefile can be used.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Therefore, if none of the default makefiles exists, `make` will try to make each of them until it succeeds in making one, or it runs out of names to try.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Note that it is not an error if `make` cannot find or make any makefile; a makefile is not always necessary.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] When you use the ‘-t’ or ‘--touch’ option (see Instead of Executing Recipes), you would not want to use an out-of-date makefile to decide which targets to touch.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] So the ‘-t’ option has no effect on updating makefiles; they are really updated even if ‘-t’ is specified.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Likewise, ‘-q’ (or ‘--question’) and ‘-n’ (or ‘--just-print’) do not prevent updating of makefiles, because an out-of-date makefile would result in the wrong output for other targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Thus, ‘make -f mfile -n foo’ will update mfile, read it in, and then print the recipe to update foo and its prerequisites without running it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The recipe printed for foo will be the one specified in the updated contents of mfile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] However, on occasion you might actually wish to prevent updating of even the makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] You can do this by specifying the makefiles as goals in the command line as well as specifying them as makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] When the makefile name is specified explicitly as a goal, the options ‘-t’ and so on do apply to them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Thus, ‘make -f mfile -n mfile foo’ would read the makefile mfile, print the recipe needed to update it without actually running it, and then print the recipe needed to update foo without running that.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The recipe for foo will be the one specified by the existing contents of mfile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Sometimes it is useful to have a makefile that is mostly just like another makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] You can often use the ‘include’ directive to include one in the other, and add more targets or variable definitions.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] However, it is invalid for two makefiles to give different recipes for the same target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In the containing makefile (the one that wants to include the other), you can use a match-anything pattern rule to say that to remake any target that cannot be made from the information in the containing makefile, `make` should look in another makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] See Defining and Redefining Pattern Rules, for more information on pattern rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you say ‘make foo’, `make` will find GNUmakefile, read it, and see that to make foo, it needs to run the recipe ‘frobnicate > foo’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you say ‘make bar’, `make` will find no way to make bar in GNUmakefile, so it will use the recipe from the pattern rule: ‘make -f Makefile bar’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If Makefile provides a rule for updating bar, `make` will apply the rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] And likewise for any other target that GNUmakefile does not say how to make.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The way this works is that the pattern rule has a pattern of just ‘%’, so it matches any target whatever.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The rule specifies a prerequisite force, to guarantee that the recipe will be run even if the target file already exists.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] We give the force target an empty recipe to prevent `make` from searching for an implicit rule to build it—otherwise it would apply the same match-anything rule to force itself and create a prerequisite loop!
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] GNU `make` does its work in two distinct phases.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] During the first phase it reads all the makefiles, included makefiles, etc. and internalizes all the variables and their values and implicit and explicit rules, and builds a dependency graph of all the targets and their prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] During the second phase, `make` uses this internalized data to determine which targets need to be updated and run the recipes necessary to update them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] It’s important to understand this two-phase approach because it has a direct impact on how variable and function expansion happens; this is often a source of some confusion when writing makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Below is a summary of the different constructs that can be found in a makefile, and the phase in which expansion happens for each part of the construct.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] We say that expansion is *immediate* if it happens during the first phase: `make` will expand that part of the construct as the makefile is parsed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] We say that expansion is *deferred* if it is not immediate.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Expansion of a deferred construct part is delayed until the expansion is used: either when it is referenced in an immediate context, or when it is needed during the second phase.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] You may not be familiar with some of these constructs yet.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] You can reference this section as you become familiar with them, in later chapters.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] For the append operator ‘+=’, the right-hand side is considered immediate if the variable was previously set as a simple variable (‘:=’ or ‘::=’), and deferred otherwise.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] For the *immediate-with-escape* operator ‘:::=’, the value on the right-hand side is immediately expanded but then escaped (that is, all instances of `$` in the result of the expansion are replaced with `$$`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] For the shell assignment operator ‘!=’, the right-hand side is evaluated immediately and handed to the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The result is stored in the variable named on the left, and that variable is considered a recursively expanded variable (and will thus be re-evaluated on each reference).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Conditional directives are parsed immediately.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This means, for example, that automatic variables cannot be used in conditional directives, as automatic variables are not set until the recipe for that rule is invoked.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you need to use automatic variables in a conditional directive you *must* move the condition into the recipe and use shell conditional syntax instead.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] That is, the target and prerequisite sections are expanded immediately, and the recipe used to build the target is always deferred.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This is true for explicit rules, pattern rules, suffix rules, static pattern rules, and simple prerequisite definitions.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] GNU `make` parses makefiles line-by-line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Remove comments (see What Makefiles Contain).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If the line begins with the recipe prefix character and we are in a rule context, add the line to the current recipe and read the next line (see Recipe Syntax).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Expand elements of the line which appear in an *immediate* expansion context (see How `make` Reads a Makefile).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Scan the line for a separator character, such as ‘:’ or ‘=’, to determine whether the line is a macro assignment or a rule (see Recipe Syntax).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Internalize the resulting operation and read the next line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] An important consequence of this is that a macro can expand to an entire rule, *if it is one line long*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The above makefile results in the definition of a target ‘target’ with prerequisites ‘echo’ and ‘built’, as if the makefile contained `target: echo built`, rather than a rule with a recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Newlines still present in a line after expansion is complete are ignored as normal whitespace.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In order to properly expand a multi-line macro you must use the `eval` function: this causes the `make` parser to be run on the results of the expanded macro (see The `eval` Function).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Previously we learned that GNU `make` works in two distinct phases: a read-in phase and a target-update phase (see How `make` Reads a Makefile).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] GNU Make also has the ability to enable a *second expansion* of the prerequisites (only) for some or all targets defined in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In order for this second expansion to occur, the special target `.SECONDEXPANSION` must be defined before the first prerequisite list that makes use of this feature.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If `.SECONDEXPANSION` is defined then when GNU `make` needs to check the prerequisites of a target, the prerequisites are expanded a *second time*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In most circumstances this secondary expansion will have no effect, since all variable and function references will have been expanded during the initial parsing of the makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In order to take advantage of the secondary expansion phase of the parser, then, it’s necessary to *escape* the variable or function reference in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In this case the first expansion merely un-escapes the reference but doesn’t expand it, and expansion is left to the secondary expansion phase.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] After the first expansion phase the prerequisites list of the myfile target will be `onefile` and `$(TWOVAR)`; the first (unescaped) variable reference to *ONEVAR* is expanded, while the second (escaped) variable reference is simply unescaped, without being recognized as a variable reference.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Now during the secondary expansion the first word is expanded again but since it contains no variable or function references it remains the value onefile, while the second word is now a normal reference to the variable *TWOVAR*, which is expanded to the value twofile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The final result is that there are two prerequisites, onefile and twofile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Obviously, this is not a very interesting case since the same result could more easily have been achieved simply by having both variables appear, unescaped, in the prerequisites list.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Here the prerequisite of onefile will be expanded immediately, and resolve to the value top, while the prerequisite of twofile will not be full expanded until the secondary expansion and yield a value of bottom.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This is marginally more exciting, but the true power of this feature only becomes apparent when you discover that secondary expansions always take place within the scope of the automatic variables for that target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This means that you can use variables such as `$@`, `$*`, etc. during the second expansion and they will have their expected values, just as in the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] All you have to do is defer the expansion by escaping the `$`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Also, secondary expansion occurs for both explicit and implicit (pattern) rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Knowing this, the possible uses for this feature increase dramatically.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Here, after the initial expansion the prerequisites of both the main and lib targets will be `$($@_OBJS)`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] During the secondary expansion, the `$@` variable is set to the name of the target and so the expansion for the main target will yield `$(main_OBJS)`, or `main.o try.o test.o`, while the secondary expansion for the lib target will yield `$(lib_OBJS)`, or `lib.o api.o`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] This version allows users to specify source files rather than object files, but gives the same resulting prerequisites list as the previous example.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Evaluation of automatic variables during the secondary expansion phase, especially of the target name variable `$$@`, behaves similarly to evaluation within recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] However, there are some subtle differences and “corner cases” which come into play for the different types of rule definitions that `make` understands.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The subtleties of using the different automatic variables are described below.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] During the secondary expansion of explicit rules, `$$@` and `$$%` evaluate, respectively, to the file name of the target and, when the target is an archive member, the target member name.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The `$$<` variable evaluates to the first prerequisite in the first rule for this target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] `$$^` and `$$+` evaluate to the list of all prerequisites of rules *that have already appeared* for the same target (`$$+` with repetitions and `$$^` without).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In the first prerequisite list, all three variables (`$$<`, `$$^`, and `$$+`) expand to the empty string.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In the second, they will have values `foo.1`, `foo.1 bar.1`, and `foo.1 bar.1` respectively.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] In the third they will have values `foo.1`, `foo.1 bar.1 foo.2 bar.2`, and `foo.1 bar.1 foo.2 bar.2 foo.1 foo.1 bar.1 foo.1 bar.1` respectively.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Rules undergo secondary expansion in makefile order, except that the rule with the recipe is always evaluated last.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The variables `$$?` and `$$*` are not available and expand to the empty string.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Rules for secondary expansion of static pattern rules are identical to those for explicit rules, above, with one exception: for static pattern rules the `$$*` variable is set to the pattern stem.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] As with explicit rules, `$$?` is not available and expands to the empty string.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] As `make` searches for an implicit rule, it substitutes the stem and then performs secondary expansion for every rule with a matching target pattern.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The value of the automatic variables is derived in the same fashion as for static pattern rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] When the implicit rule is tried for target foo, `$$<` expands to bar, `$$^` expands to bar boo, `$$+` also expands to bar boo, and `$$*` expands to f.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] Note that the directory prefix (D), as described in Implicit Rule Search Algorithm, is appended (after expansion) to all the patterns in the prerequisites list.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] The prerequisite list printed, after the secondary expansion and directory prefix reconstruction, will be /tmp/foo/foo.c /tmp/bar/foo.c foo.h.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p02] If you are not interested in this reconstruction, you can use `$$*` instead of `%` in the prerequisites list.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] A *rule* appears in the makefile and says when and how to remake certain files, called the rule’s *targets* (most often only one per rule).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] It lists the other files that are the *prerequisites* of the target, and the *recipe* to use to create or update the target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The order of rules is not significant, except for determining the *default goal*: the target for `make` to consider, if you do not otherwise specify one.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The default goal is the first target of the first rule in the first makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] There are two exceptions: a target starting with a period is not a default unless it also contains one or more slashes, ‘/’; and, a target that defines a pattern rule has no effect on the default goal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Therefore, we usually write the makefile so that the first rule is the one for compiling the entire program or all the programs described by the makefile (often with a target called ‘all’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Its target is foo.o and its prerequisites are foo.c and defs.h.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] It has one command in the recipe: ‘cc -c -g foo.c’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The recipe starts with a tab to identify it as a recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The *targets* are file names, separated by spaces.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcard characters may be used (see Using Wildcard Characters in File Names) and a name of the form *a*(*m*) represents member *m* in archive file *a* (see Archive Members as Targets).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Usually there is only one target per rule, but occasionally there is a reason to have more (see Multiple Targets in a Rule).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The *recipe* lines start with a tab character (or the first character in the value of the `.RECIPEPREFIX` variable; see Other Special Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The first recipe line may appear on the line after the prerequisites, with a tab character, or may appear on the same line, with a semicolon.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] There are other differences in the syntax of recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Because dollar signs are used to start `make` variable references, if you really want a dollar sign in a target or prerequisite you must write two of them, ‘$$’ (see How to Use Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If you have enabled secondary expansion (see Secondary Expansion) and you want a literal dollar sign in the prerequisites list, you must actually write *four* dollar signs (‘$$$$’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] You may split a long line by inserting a backslash followed by a newline, but this is not required, as `make` places no limit on the length of a line in a makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] A rule tells `make` two things: when the targets are out of date, and how to update them when necessary.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The criterion for being out of date is specified in terms of the *prerequisites*, which consist of file names separated by spaces.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] (Wildcards and archive members (see Using `make` to Update Archive Files) are allowed here too.) A target is out of date if it does not exist or if it is older than any of the prerequisites (by comparison of last-modification times).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The idea is that the contents of the target file are computed based on information in the prerequisites, so if any of the prerequisites changes, the contents of the existing target file are no longer necessarily valid.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] How to update is specified by a *recipe*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This is one or more lines to be executed by the shell (normally ‘sh’), but with some extra features (see Writing Recipes in Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] There are two different types of prerequisites understood by GNU `make`: normal prerequisites, described in the previous section, and *order-only* prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] A normal prerequisite makes two statements: first, it imposes an order in which recipes will be invoked: the recipes for all prerequisites of a target will be completed before the recipe for the target is started.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Second, it imposes a dependency relationship: if any prerequisite is newer than the target, then the target is considered out-of-date and must be rebuilt.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Normally, this is exactly what you want: if a target’s prerequisite is updated, then the target should also be updated.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Occasionally you may want to ensure that a prerequisite is built before a target, but *without* forcing the target to be updated if the prerequisite is updated.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] *Order-only* prerequisites are used to create this type of relationship.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The normal prerequisites section may of course be empty.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Also, you may still declare multiple lines of prerequisites for the same target: they are appended appropriately (normal prerequisites are appended to the list of normal prerequisites; order-only prerequisites are appended to the list of order-only prerequisites).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Note that if you declare the same file to be both a normal and an order-only prerequisite, the normal prerequisite takes precedence (since they have a strict superset of the behavior of an order-only prerequisite).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Order-only prerequisites are never checked when determining if the target is out of date; even order-only prerequisites marked as phony (see Phony Targets) will not cause the target to be rebuilt.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Consider an example where your targets are to be placed in a separate directory, and that directory might not exist before `make` is run.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] In this situation, you want the directory to be created before any targets are placed into it but, because the timestamps on directories change whenever a file is added, removed, or renamed, we certainly don’t want to rebuild all the targets whenever the directory’s timestamp changes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Now the rule to create the objdir directory will be run, if needed, before any ‘.o’ is built, but no ‘.o’ will be built because the objdir directory timestamp changed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] A single file name can specify many files using *wildcard characters*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The wildcard characters in `make` are ‘*’, ‘?’ and ‘[…]’, the same as in the Bourne shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] For example, *.c specifies a list of all the files (in the working directory) whose names end in ‘.c’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If an expression matches multiple files then the results will be sorted.2 However multiple expressions will not be globally sorted.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] For example, *.c *.h will list all the files whose names end in ‘.c’, sorted, followed by all the files whose names end in ‘.h’, sorted.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The character ‘~’ at the beginning of a file name also has special significance.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If alone, or followed by a slash, it represents your home directory.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] For example ~/bin expands to /home/you/bin.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If the ‘~’ is followed by a word, the string represents the home directory of the user named by that word.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] For example ~john/bin expands to /home/john/bin.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] On systems which don’t have a home directory for each user (such as MS-DOS or MS-Windows), this functionality can be simulated by setting the environment variable *HOME*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcard expansion is performed by `make` automatically in targets and in prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] In recipes, the shell is responsible for wildcard expansion.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] In other contexts, wildcard expansion happens only if you request it explicitly with the `wildcard` function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The special significance of a wildcard character can be turned off by preceding it with a backslash.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Thus, foo\*bar would refer to a specific file whose name consists of ‘foo’, an asterisk, and ‘bar’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcards can be used in the recipe of a rule, where they are expanded by the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcards are also useful in the prerequisites of a rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This rule uses print as an empty target file; see Empty Target Files to Record Events.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcard expansion does not happen when you define a variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] then the value of the variable `objects` is the actual string ‘*.o’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] However, if you use the value of `objects` in a target or prerequisite, wildcard expansion will take place there.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If you use the value of `objects` in a recipe, the shell may perform wildcard expansion when the recipe runs.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Now here is an example of a naive way of using wildcard expansion, that does not do what you would intend.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The value of `objects` is the actual string ‘*.o’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcard expansion happens in the rule for foo, so that each *existing* ‘.o’ file becomes a prerequisite of foo and will be recompiled if necessary.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] But what if you delete all the ‘.o’ files?
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] When a wildcard matches no files, it is left as it is, so then foo will depend on the oddly-named file *.o.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Since no such file is likely to exist, `make` will give you an error saying it cannot figure out how to make *.o.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Actually it is possible to obtain the desired result with wildcard expansion, but you need more sophisticated techniques, including the `wildcard` function and string substitution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This is equivalent to the Unix-style c:/foo/bar/baz.c (the c: part is the so-called drive letter).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] When `make` runs on these systems, it supports backslashes as well as the Unix-style forward slashes in pathnames.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] However, this support does *not* include the wildcard expansion, where backslash is a quote character.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Therefore, you *must* use Unix-style slashes in these cases.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Wildcard expansion happens automatically in rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] But wildcard expansion does not normally take place when a variable is set, or inside the arguments of a function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This string, used anywhere in a makefile, is replaced by a space-separated list of names of existing files that match one of the given file name patterns.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If no existing file name matches a pattern, then that pattern is omitted from the output of the `wildcard` function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Note that this is different from how unmatched wildcards behave in rules, where they are used verbatim rather than ignored (see Pitfalls of Using Wildcards).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] As with wildcard expansion in rules, the results of the `wildcard` function are sorted.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] But again, each individual expression is sorted separately, so ‘$(wildcard *.c *.h)’ will expand to all files matching ‘.c’, sorted, followed by all files matching ‘.h’, sorted.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] (Here we have used another function, `patsubst`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] (This takes advantage of the implicit rule for compiling C programs, so there is no need to write explicit rules for compiling the files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] A phony target is one that is not really the name of a file; rather it is just a name for a recipe to be executed when you make an explicit request.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] There are two reasons to use a phony target: to avoid a conflict with a file of the same name, and to improve performance.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If you write a rule whose recipe will not create the target file, the recipe will be executed every time the target comes up for remaking.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Because the `rm` command does not create a file named clean, probably no such file will ever exist.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Therefore, the `rm` command will be executed every time you say ‘make clean’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] In this example, the clean target will not work properly if a file named clean is ever created in this directory.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Since it has no prerequisites, clean would always be considered up to date and its recipe would not be executed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Once this is done, ‘make clean’ will run the recipe regardless of whether there is a file named clean.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Prerequisites of `.PHONY` are always interpreted as literal target names, never as patterns (even if they contain ‘%’ characters).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] To always rebuild a pattern rule consider using a “force target” (see Rules without Recipes or Prerequisites).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Phony targets are also useful in conjunction with recursive invocations of `make` (see Recursive Use of `make`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] In this situation the makefile will often contain a variable which lists a number of sub-directories to be built.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] There are problems with this method, however.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] First, any error detected in a sub-make is ignored by this rule, so it will continue to build the rest of the directories even when one fails.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This can be overcome by adding shell commands to note the error and exit, but then it will do so even if `make` is invoked with the `-k` option, which is unfortunate.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Second, and perhaps more importantly, you cannot take full advantage of `make`’s ability to build targets in parallel (see Parallel Execution), since there is only one rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Each individual makefile’s targets will be built in parallel, but only one sub-directory will be built at a time.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Here we’ve also declared that the foo sub-directory cannot be built until after the baz sub-directory is complete; this kind of relationship declaration is particularly important when attempting parallel builds.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The implicit rule search (see Using Implicit Rules) is skipped for `.PHONY` targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This is why declaring a target as `.PHONY` is good for performance, even if you are not worried about the actual file existing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] A phony target should not be a prerequisite of a real target file; if it is, its recipe will be run every time `make` considers that file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] As long as a phony target is never a prerequisite of a real target, the phony target recipe will be executed only when the phony target is a specified goal (see Arguments to Specify the Goals).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] You should not declare an included makefile as phony.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Phony targets are not intended to represent real files, and because the target is always considered out of date make will always rebuild it then re-execute itself (see How Makefiles Are Remade).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] To avoid this, `make` will not re-execute itself if an included file marked as phony is re-built.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] When one directory contains multiple programs, it is most convenient to describe all of the programs in one makefile ./Makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Since the target remade by default will be the first one in the makefile, it is common to make this a phony target named ‘all’ and give it, as prerequisites, all the individual programs.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Now you can say just ‘make’ to remake all three programs, or specify as arguments the ones to remake (as in ‘make prog1 prog3’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Phoniness is not inherited: the prerequisites of a phony target are not themselves phony, unless explicitly declared to be so.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] When one phony target is a prerequisite of another, it serves as a subroutine of the other.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] If a rule has no prerequisites or recipe, and the target of the rule is a nonexistent file, then `make` imagines this target to have been updated whenever its rule is run.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] This implies that all targets depending on this one will always have their recipe run.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Here the target ‘FORCE’ satisfies the special conditions, so the target clean that depends on it is forced to run its recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] There is nothing special about the name ‘FORCE’, but that is one name commonly used this way.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] As you can see, using ‘FORCE’ this way has the same results as using ‘.PHONY: clean’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Using ‘.PHONY’ is more explicit and more efficient.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] However, other versions of `make` do not support ‘.PHONY’; thus ‘FORCE’ appears in many makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The *empty target* is a variant of the phony target; it is used to hold recipes for an action that you request explicitly from time to time.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Unlike a phony target, this target file can really exist; but the file’s contents do not matter, and usually are empty.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The purpose of the empty target file is to record, with its last-modification time, when the rule’s recipe was last executed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] It does so because one of the commands in the recipe is a `touch` command to update the target file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The empty target file should have some prerequisites (otherwise it doesn’t make sense).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] When you ask to remake the empty target, the recipe is executed if any prerequisite is more recent than the target; in other words, if a prerequisite has changed since the last time you remade the target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] With this rule, ‘make print’ will execute the `lpr` command if either source file has changed since the last ‘make print’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The automatic variable ‘$?’ is used to print only those files that have changed (see Automatic Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] Certain names have special meanings if they appear as targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The prerequisites of the special target `.PHONY` are considered to be phony targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] When it is time to consider such a target, `make` will run its recipe unconditionally, regardless of whether a file with that name exists or what its last-modification time is.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p03] The prerequisites of the special target `.SUFFIXES` are the list of suffixes to be used in checking for suffix rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The recipe specified for `.DEFAULT` is used for any target for which no rules are found (either explicit rules or implicit rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If a `.DEFAULT` recipe is specified, every file mentioned as a prerequisite, but not as a target in a rule, will have that recipe executed on its behalf.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The targets which `.PRECIOUS` depends on are given the following special treatment: if `make` is killed or interrupted during the execution of their recipes, the target is not deleted.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Also, if the target is an intermediate file, it will not be deleted after it is no longer needed, as is normally done.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In this latter respect it overlaps with the `.SECONDARY` special target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] You can also list the target pattern of an implicit rule (such as ‘%.o’) as a prerequisite file of the special target `.PRECIOUS` to preserve intermediate files created by rules whose target patterns match that file’s name.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The targets which `.INTERMEDIATE` depends on are treated as intermediate files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] `.INTERMEDIATE` with no prerequisites has no effect.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Prerequisites of the special target `.NOTINTERMEDIATE` are never considered intermediate files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] `.NOTINTERMEDIATE` with no prerequisites causes all targets to be treated as not intermediate.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If the prerequisite is a target pattern then targets that are built using that pattern rule are not considered intermediate.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The targets which `.SECONDARY` depends on are treated as intermediate files, except that they are never automatically deleted.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] `.SECONDARY` can be used to avoid redundant rebuilds in some unusual situations.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Suppose hello.bin is up to date in regards to the source files, *but* the object file hello.o is missing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Without `.SECONDARY` make would rebuild hello.o then rebuild hello.bin even though the source files had not changed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] By declaring hello.o as `.SECONDARY` `make` will not need to rebuild it and won’t need to rebuild hello.bin either.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Of course, if one of the source files *were* updated then all object files would be rebuilt so that the creation of hello.bin could succeed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] `.SECONDARY` with no prerequisites causes all targets to be treated as secondary (i.e., no target is removed because it is considered intermediate).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If `.SECONDEXPANSION` is mentioned as a target anywhere in the makefile, then all prerequisite lists defined *after* it appears will be expanded a second time after all makefiles have been read in.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If `.DELETE_ON_ERROR` is mentioned as a target anywhere in the makefile, then `make` will delete the target of a rule if it has changed and its recipe exits with a nonzero exit status, just as it does when it receives a signal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If you specify prerequisites for `.IGNORE`, then `make` will ignore errors in execution of the recipe for those particular files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The recipe for `.IGNORE` (if any) is ignored.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If mentioned as a target with no prerequisites, `.IGNORE` says to ignore errors in execution of recipes for all files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This usage of ‘.IGNORE’ is supported only for historical compatibility.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Since this affects every recipe in the makefile, it is not very useful; we recommend you use the more selective ways to ignore errors in specific recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If you specify prerequisites for `.LOW_RESOLUTION_TIME`, `make` assumes that these files are created by commands that generate low resolution time stamps.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The recipe for the `.LOW_RESOLUTION_TIME` target are ignored.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The high resolution file time stamps of many modern file systems lessen the chance of `make` incorrectly concluding that a file is up to date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Unfortunately, some hosts do not provide a way to set a high resolution file time stamp, so commands like ‘cp -p’ that explicitly set a file’s time stamp must discard its sub-second part.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If a file is created by such a command, you should list it as a prerequisite of `.LOW_RESOLUTION_TIME` so that `make` does not mistakenly conclude that the file is out of date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Since ‘cp -p’ discards the sub-second part of src’s time stamp, dst is typically slightly older than src even when it is up to date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The `.LOW_RESOLUTION_TIME` line causes `make` to consider dst to be up to date if its time stamp is at the start of the same second that src’s time stamp is in.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Due to a limitation of the archive format, archive member time stamps are always low resolution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] You need not list archive members as prerequisites of `.LOW_RESOLUTION_TIME`, as `make` does this automatically.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If you specify prerequisites for `.SILENT`, then `make` will not print the recipe used to remake those particular files before executing them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If mentioned as a target with no prerequisites, `.SILENT` says not to print any recipes before executing them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] You may also use more selective ways to silence specific recipe command lines.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If you want to silence all recipes for a particular run of `make`, use the ‘-s’ or ‘--silent’ option (see Summary of Options).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Simply by being mentioned as a target, this tells `make` to export all variables to child processes by default.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This is an alternative to using `export` with no arguments.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] See Communicating Variables to a Sub-`make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If `.NOTPARALLEL` is mentioned as a target with no prerequisites, all targets in this invocation of `make` will be run serially, even if the ‘-j’ option is given.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Any recursively invoked `make` command will still run recipes in parallel (unless its makefile also contains this target).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If `.NOTPARALLEL` has targets as prerequisites, then all the prerequisites of those targets will be run serially.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This implicitly adds a `.WAIT` between each prerequisite of the listed targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If `.ONESHELL` is mentioned as a target, then when a target is built all lines of the recipe will be given to a single invocation of the shell rather than each line being invoked separately.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If `.POSIX` is mentioned as a target, then the makefile will be parsed and run in POSIX-conforming mode.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This does *not* mean that only POSIX-conforming makefiles will be accepted: all advanced GNU `make` features are still available.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Rather, this target causes `make` to behave as required by POSIX in those areas where `make`’s default behavior differs.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In particular, if this target is mentioned then recipes will be invoked as if the shell had been passed the `-e` flag: the first failing command in a recipe will cause the recipe to fail immediately.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Any defined implicit rule suffix also counts as a special target if it appears as a target, and so does the concatenation of two suffixes, such as ‘.c.o’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] These targets are suffix rules, an obsolete way of defining implicit rules (but a way still widely used).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In principle, any target name could be special in this way if you break it in two and add both pieces to the suffix list.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In practice, suffixes normally begin with ‘.’, so these special target names also begin with ‘.’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] When an explicit rule has multiple targets they can be treated in one of two possible ways: as independent targets or as grouped targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The manner in which they are treated is determined by the separator that appears after the list of targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Rules that use the standard target separator, `:`, define independent targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This is equivalent to writing the same rule once for each target, with duplicated prerequisites and recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Typically, the recipe would use automatic variables such as ‘$@’ to specify which target is being built.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Suppose you would like to vary the prerequisites according to the target, much as the variable ‘$@’ allows you to vary the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] You cannot do this with multiple targets in an ordinary rule, but you can do it with a *static pattern rule*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If instead of independent targets you have a recipe that generates multiple files from a single invocation, you can express that relationship by declaring your rule to use *grouped targets*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] A grouped target rule uses the separator `&:` (the ‘&’ here is used to imply “all”).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] When `make` builds any one of the grouped targets, it understands that all the other targets in the group are also updated as a result of the invocation of the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Furthermore, if only some of the grouped targets are out of date or missing `make` will realize that running the recipe will update all of the targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Finally, if any of the grouped targets are out of date, all the grouped targets are considered out of date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] During the execution of a grouped target’s recipe, the automatic variable ‘$@’ is set to the name of the particular target in the group which triggered the rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Caution must be used if relying on this variable in the recipe of a grouped target rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Unlike independent targets, a grouped target rule *must* include a recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] However, targets that are members of a grouped target may also appear in independent target rule definitions that do not have recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each target may have only one recipe associated with it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If a grouped target appears in either an independent target rule or in another grouped target rule with a recipe, you will get a warning and the latter recipe will replace the former recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Additionally the target will be removed from the previous group and appear only in the new group.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If you would like a target to appear in multiple groups, then you must use the double-colon grouped target separator, `&::` when declaring all of the groups containing that target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Grouped double-colon targets are each considered independently, and each grouped double-colon rule’s recipe is executed at most once, if at least one of its multiple targets requires updating.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] One file can be the target of several rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] All the prerequisites mentioned in all the rules are merged into one list of prerequisites for the target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If the target is older than any prerequisite from any rule, the recipe is executed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] There can only be one recipe to be executed for a file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If more than one rule gives a recipe for the same file, `make` uses the last one given and prints an error message.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] (As a special case, if the file’s name begins with a dot, no error message is printed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This odd behavior is only for compatibility with other implementations of `make`… you should avoid using it).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Occasionally it is useful to have the same target invoke multiple recipes which are defined in different parts of your makefile; you can use *double-colon rules* (see Double-Colon Rules) for this.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] An extra rule with just prerequisites can be used to give a few extra prerequisites to many files at once.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] For example, makefiles often have a variable, such as `objects`, containing a list of all the compiler output files in the system being made.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This could be inserted or taken out without changing the rules that really specify how to make the object files, making it a convenient form to use if you wish to add the additional prerequisite intermittently.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Another wrinkle is that the additional prerequisites could be specified with a variable that you set with a command line argument to `make` (see Overriding Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] means that the command ‘make extradeps=foo.h’ will consider foo.h as a prerequisite of each object file, but plain ‘make’ will not.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If none of the explicit rules for a target has a recipe, then `make` searches for an applicable implicit rule to find one see Using Implicit Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The *targets* list specifies the targets that the rule applies to.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The targets can contain wildcard characters, just like the targets of ordinary rules (see Using Wildcard Characters in File Names).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The *target-pattern* and *prereq-patterns* say how to compute the prerequisites of each target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each target is matched against the *target-pattern* to extract a part of the target name, called the *stem*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This stem is substituted into each of the *prereq-patterns* to make the prerequisite names (one from each *prereq-pattern*).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each pattern normally contains the character ‘%’ just once.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] When the *target-pattern* matches a target, the ‘%’ can match any part of the target name; this part is called the *stem*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The rest of the pattern must match exactly.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] For example, the target foo.o matches the pattern ‘%.o’, with ‘foo’ as the stem.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The targets foo.c and foo.out do not match that pattern.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The prerequisite names for each target are made by substituting the stem for the ‘%’ in each prerequisite pattern.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] For example, if one prerequisite pattern is %.c, then substitution of the stem ‘foo’ gives the prerequisite name foo.c.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] It is legitimate to write a prerequisite pattern that does not contain ‘%’; then this prerequisite is the same for all targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] ‘%’ characters in pattern rules can be quoted with preceding backslashes (‘\’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Backslashes that would otherwise quote ‘%’ characters can be quoted with more backslashes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Backslashes that quote ‘%’ characters or other backslashes are removed from the pattern before it is compared to file names or has a stem substituted into it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Backslashes that are not in danger of quoting ‘%’ characters go unmolested.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] For example, the pattern the\%weird\\%pattern\\ has ‘the%weird\’ preceding the operative ‘%’ character, and ‘pattern\\’ following it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The final two backslashes are left alone because they cannot affect any ‘%’ character.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Here ‘$<’ is the automatic variable that holds the name of the prerequisite and ‘$@’ is the automatic variable that holds the name of the target; see Automatic Variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each target specified must match the target pattern; a warning is issued for each target that does not.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In this example the result of ‘$(filter %.o,$(files))’ is bar.o lose.o, and the first static pattern rule causes each of these object files to be updated by compiling the corresponding C source file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The result of ‘$(filter %.elc,$(files))’ is foo.elc, so that file is made from foo.el.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] When the `generate` command is run, `$*` will expand to the stem, either ‘big’ or ‘little’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] A static pattern rule has much in common with an implicit rule defined as a pattern rule (see Defining and Redefining Pattern Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Both have a pattern for the target and patterns for constructing the names of prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The difference is in how `make` decides *when* the rule applies.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] An implicit rule *can* apply to any target that matches its pattern, but it *does* apply only when the target has no recipe otherwise specified, and only when the prerequisites can be found.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If more than one implicit rule appears applicable, only one applies; the choice depends on the order of rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] By contrast, a static pattern rule applies to the precise list of targets that you specify in the rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] It cannot apply to any other target and it invariably does apply to each of the targets specified.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If two conflicting rules apply, and both have recipes, that’s an error.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] When a target appears in multiple rules, all the rules must be the same type: all ordinary, or all double-colon.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If they are double-colon, each of them is independent of the others.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each double-colon rule’s recipe is executed if the target is older than any prerequisites of that rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] If there are no prerequisites for that rule, its recipe is always executed (even if the target already exists).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This can result in executing none, any, or all of the double-colon rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Double-colon rules with the same target are in fact completely separate from one another.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each double-colon rule is processed individually, just as rules with different targets are processed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The double-colon rules for a target are executed in the order they appear in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] However, the cases where double-colon rules really make sense are those where the order of executing the recipes would not matter.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Double-colon rules are somewhat obscure and not often very useful; they provide a mechanism for cases in which the method used to update a target differs depending on which prerequisite files caused the update, and such cases are rare.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Each double-colon rule should specify a recipe; if it does not, an implicit rule will be used if one applies.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In the makefile for a program, many of the rules you need to write often say only that some object file depends on some header file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] You need this rule so that `make` knows that it must remake main.o whenever defs.h changes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] You can see that for a large program you would have to write dozens of such rules in your makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] And, you must always be very careful to update the makefile every time you add or remove an `#include`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] To avoid this hassle, most modern C compilers can write these rules for you, by looking at the `#include` lines in the source files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Usually this is done with the ‘-M’ option to the compiler.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Thus you no longer have to write all those rules yourself.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Note that such a rule constitutes mentioning main.o in a makefile, so it can never be considered an intermediate file by implicit rule search.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This means that `make` won’t ever remove the file after using it; see Chains of Implicit Rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] With old `make` programs, it was traditional practice to use this compiler feature to generate prerequisites on demand with a command like ‘make depend’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] That command would create a file depend containing all the automatically-generated prerequisites; then the makefile could use `include` to read them in (see Including Other Makefiles).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] In GNU `make`, the feature of remaking makefiles makes this practice obsolete—you need never tell `make` explicitly to regenerate the prerequisites, because it always regenerates any makefile that is out of date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The practice we recommend for automatic prerequisite generation is to have one makefile corresponding to each source file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] For each source file *name*.c there is a makefile *name*.d which lists what files the object file *name*.o depends on.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] That way only the source files that have changed need to be rescanned to produce the new prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] See Defining and Redefining Pattern Rules, for information on defining pattern rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] The ‘-e’ flag to the shell causes it to exit immediately if the `$(CC)` command (or any other command) fails (exits with a nonzero status).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] With the GNU C compiler, you may wish to use the ‘-MM’ flag instead of ‘-M’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This omits prerequisites on system header files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] See Options Controlling the Preprocessor in *Using GNU CC*, for details.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] This makes each ‘.d’ file depend on all the source and header files that the corresponding ‘.o’ file depends on.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] `make` then knows it must regenerate the prerequisites whenever any of the source or header files changes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Once you’ve defined the rule to remake the ‘.d’ files, you then use the `include` directive to read them all in.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] (This example uses a substitution variable reference to translate the list of source files ‘foo.c bar.c’ into a list of prerequisite makefiles, ‘foo.d bar.d’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] See Substitution References, for full information on substitution references.) Since the ‘.d’ files are makefiles like any others, `make` will remake them as necessary with no further work from you.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p04] Note that the ‘.d’ files contain target definitions; you should be sure to place the `include` directive *after* the first, default goal in your makefiles or run the risk of having a random object file become the default goal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The recipe of a rule consists of one or more shell command lines to be executed, one at a time, in the order they appear.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Typically, the result of executing these commands is that the target of the rule is brought up to date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Users use many different shell programs, but recipes in makefiles are always interpreted by /bin/sh unless the makefile specifies otherwise.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Makefiles have the unusual property that there are really two distinct syntaxes in one file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Most of the makefile uses `make` syntax (see Writing Makefiles).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However, recipes are meant to be interpreted by the shell and so they are written using shell syntax.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The `make` program does not try to understand shell syntax: it performs only a very few specific translations on the content of the recipe before handing it to the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Each line in the recipe must start with a tab (or the first character in the value of the `.RECIPEPREFIX` variable; see Other Special Variables), except that the first recipe line may be attached to the target-and-prerequisites line with a semicolon in between.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] *Any* line in the makefile that begins with a tab and appears in a “rule context” (that is, after a rule has been started until another rule or variable definition) will be considered part of a recipe for that rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Blank lines and lines of just comments may appear among the recipe lines; they are ignored.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] One of the few ways in which `make` does interpret recipes is checking for a backslash just before the newline.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] As in normal makefile syntax, a single logical recipe line can be split into multiple physical lines in the makefile by placing a backslash before each newline.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] A sequence of lines like this is considered a single recipe line, and one instance of the shell will be invoked to run it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However, in contrast to how they are treated in other places in a makefile (see Splitting Long Lines), backslash/newline pairs are *not* removed from the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Both the backslash and the newline characters are preserved and passed to the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] How the backslash/newline is interpreted depends on your shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the first character of the next line after the backslash/newline is the recipe prefix character (a tab by default; see Other Special Variables), then that character (and only that character) is removed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Whitespace is never added to the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Notice how the backslash/newline pair was removed inside the string quoted with double quotes (`"…"`), but not from the string quoted with single quotes (`'…'`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is the way the default shell (/bin/sh) handles backslash/newline pairs.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you specify a different shell in your makefiles it may treat them differently.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Sometimes you want to split a long line inside of single quotes, but you don’t want the backslash/newline to appear in the quoted content.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is often the case when passing scripts to languages such as Perl, where extraneous backslashes inside the script can change its meaning or even be a syntax error.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] One simple way of handling this is to place the quoted string, or even the entire command, into a `make` variable then use the variable in the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] In this situation the newline quoting rules for makefiles will be used, and the backslash/newline will be removed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you like, you can also use target-specific variables (see Target-specific Variable Values) to obtain a tighter correspondence between the variable and the recipe that uses it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The other way in which `make` processes recipes is by expanding any variable references in them (see Basics of Variable References).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This occurs after make has finished reading all the makefiles and the target is determined to be out of date; so, the recipes for targets which are not rebuilt are never expanded.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Variable and function references in recipes have identical syntax and semantics to references elsewhere in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] They also have the same quoting rules: if you want a dollar sign to appear in your recipe, you must double it (‘$$’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] For shells like the default shell, that use dollar signs to introduce variables, it’s important to keep clear in your mind whether the variable you want to reference is a `make` variable (use a single dollar sign) or a shell variable (use two dollar signs).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Normally `make` prints each line of the recipe before it is executed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] We call this *echoing* because it gives the appearance that you are typing the lines yourself.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] When a line starts with ‘@’, the echoing of that line is suppressed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘@’ is discarded before the line is passed to the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] When `make` is given the flag ‘-n’ or ‘--just-print’ it only echoes most recipes, without executing them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] In this case even the recipe lines starting with ‘@’ are printed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This flag is useful for finding out which recipes `make` thinks are necessary without actually doing them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘-s’ or ‘--silent’ flag to `make` prevents all echoing, as if all recipes started with ‘@’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] A rule in the makefile for the special target `.SILENT` without prerequisites has the same effect (see Special Built-in Target Names).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Here we use the shell AND operator (`&&`) so that if the `cd` command fails, the script will fail without trying to invoke the `gobble` command in the wrong directory, which could cause problems (in this case it would certainly cause ../foo to be truncated, at least).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Sometimes you would prefer that all the lines in the recipe be passed to a single invocation of the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] There are generally two situations where this is useful: first, it can improve performance in makefiles where recipes consist of many command lines, by avoiding extra processes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Second, you might want newlines to be included in your recipe command (for example perhaps you are using a very different interpreter as your `SHELL`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the `.ONESHELL` special target appears anywhere in the makefile then *all* recipe lines for each target will be provided to a single invocation of the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Newlines between recipe lines will be preserved.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] would now work as expected even though the commands are on different recipe lines.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If `.ONESHELL` is provided, then only the first line of the recipe will be checked for the special prefix characters (‘@’, ‘-’, and ‘+’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Subsequent lines will include the special characters in the recipe line when the `SHELL` is invoked.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you want your recipe to start with one of these special characters you’ll need to arrange for them to not be the first characters on the first line, perhaps by adding a comment or similar.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] As a special feature, if `SHELL` is determined to be a POSIX-style shell, the special prefix characters in “internal” recipe lines will be *removed* before the recipe is processed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This feature is intended to allow existing makefiles to add the `.ONESHELL` special target and still run properly without extensive modifications.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Since the special prefix characters are not legal at the beginning of a line in a POSIX shell script this is not a loss in functionality.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Even with this special feature, however, makefiles with `.ONESHELL` will behave differently in ways that could be noticeable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] For example, normally if any line in the recipe fails, that causes the rule to fail and no more recipe lines are processed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Under `.ONESHELL` a failure of any but the final recipe line will not be noticed by `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] You can modify `.SHELLFLAGS` to add the `-e` option to the shell which will cause any failure anywhere in the command line to cause the shell to fail, but this could itself cause your recipe to behave differently.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Ultimately you may need to harden your recipe lines to allow them to work with `.ONESHELL`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The program used as the shell is taken from the variable `SHELL`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If this variable is not set in your makefile, the program /bin/sh is used as the shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The argument(s) passed to the shell are taken from the variable `.SHELLFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The default value of `.SHELLFLAGS` is `-c` normally, or `-ec` in POSIX-conforming mode.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Unlike most variables, the variable `SHELL` is never set from the environment.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is because the `SHELL` environment variable is used to specify your personal choice of shell program for interactive use.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] It would be very bad for personal choices like this to affect the functioning of makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Furthermore, when you do set `SHELL` in your makefile that value is *not* exported in the environment to recipe lines that `make` invokes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Instead, the value inherited from the user’s environment, if any, is exported.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] You can override this behavior by explicitly exporting `SHELL` (see Communicating Variables to a Sub-`make`), forcing it to be passed in the environment to recipe lines.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However, on MS-DOS and MS-Windows the value of `SHELL` in the environment **is** used, since on those systems most users do not set this variable, and therefore it is most likely set specifically to be used by `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] On MS-DOS, if the setting of `SHELL` is not suitable for `make`, you can set the variable `MAKESHELL` to the shell that `make` should use; if set it will be used as the shell instead of the value of `SHELL`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Choosing a shell in MS-DOS and MS-Windows is much more complex than on other systems.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] On MS-DOS, if `SHELL` is not set, the value of the variable `COMSPEC` (which is always set) is used instead.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The processing of lines that set the variable `SHELL` in Makefiles is different on MS-DOS.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The stock shell, command.com, is ridiculously limited in its functionality and many users of `make` tend to install a replacement shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Therefore, on MS-DOS, `make` examines the value of `SHELL`, and changes its behavior based on whether it points to a Unix-style or DOS-style shell.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This allows reasonable functionality even if `SHELL` points to command.com.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If `SHELL` points to a Unix-style shell, `make` on MS-DOS additionally checks whether that shell can indeed be found; if not, it ignores the line that sets `SHELL`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] In each of the directories in the `PATH` variable, in order.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] In every directory it examines, `make` will first look for the specific file (sh in the example above).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If this is not found, it will also look in that directory for that file with one of the known extensions which identify executable files.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] For example .exe, .com, .bat, .btm, .sh, and some others.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If any of these attempts is successful, the value of `SHELL` will be set to the full pathname of the shell as found.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However, if none of these is found, the value of `SHELL` will not be changed, and thus the line that sets it will be effectively ignored.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is so `make` will only support features specific to a Unix-style shell if such a shell is actually installed on the system where `make` runs.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Note that this extended search for the shell is limited to the cases where `SHELL` is set from the Makefile; if it is set in the environment or command line, you are expected to set it to the full pathname of the shell, exactly as things are on Unix.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The effect of the above DOS-specific processing is that a Makefile that contains ‘SHELL = /bin/sh’ (as many Unix makefiles do), will work on MS-DOS unaltered if you have e.g. sh.exe installed in some directory along your `PATH`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] GNU `make` knows how to execute several recipes at once.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Normally, `make` will execute only one recipe at a time, waiting for it to finish before executing the next.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However, the ‘-j’ or ‘--jobs’ option tells `make` to execute many recipes simultaneously.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] You can inhibit parallelism for some or all targets from within the makefile (see Disabling Parallel Execution).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] On MS-DOS, the ‘-j’ option has no effect, since that system doesn’t support multi-processing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the ‘-j’ option is followed by an integer, this is the number of recipes to execute at once; this is called the number of *job slots*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If there is nothing looking like an integer after the ‘-j’ option, there is no limit on the number of job slots.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The default number of job slots is one, which means serial execution (one thing at a time).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Handling recursive `make` invocations raises issues for parallel execution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] For more information on this, see Communicating Options to a Sub-`make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If a recipe fails (is killed by a signal or exits with a nonzero status), and errors are not ignored for that recipe (see Errors in Recipes), the remaining recipe lines to remake the same target will not be run.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If a recipe fails and the ‘-k’ or ‘--keep-going’ option was not given (see Summary of Options), `make` aborts execution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If make terminates for any reason (including a signal) with child processes running, it waits for them to finish before actually exiting.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] When the system is heavily loaded, you will probably want to run fewer jobs than when it is lightly loaded.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] You can use the ‘-l’ option to tell `make` to limit the number of jobs to run at once, based on the load average.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘-l’ or ‘--max-load’ option is followed by a floating-point number.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] will not let `make` start more than one job if the load average is above 2.5.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘-l’ option with no following number removes the load limit, if one was given with a previous ‘-l’ option.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] More precisely, when `make` goes to start up a job, and it already has at least one job running, it checks the current load average; if it is not lower than the limit given with ‘-l’, `make` waits until the load average goes below that limit, or until all the other jobs finish.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If a makefile completely and accurately defines the dependency relationships between all of its targets, then `make` will correctly build the goals regardless of whether parallel execution is enabled or not.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is the ideal way to write makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However, sometimes some or all of the targets in a makefile cannot be executed in parallel and it’s not feasible to add the prerequisites needed to inform `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] In that case the makefile can use various methods to disable parallel execution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the `.NOTPARALLEL` special target with no prerequisites is specified anywhere then the entire instance of `make` will be run serially, regardless of the parallel setting.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Regardless of how `make` is invoked, the targets one, two, and three will be run serially.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the `.NOTPARALLEL` special target has prerequisites, then each of those prerequisites will be considered a target and all prerequisites of these targets will be run serially.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Note that only when building this target will the prerequisites be run serially: if some other target lists the same prerequisites and is not in `.NOTPARALLEL` then these prerequisites may be run in parallel.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Here ‘make -j base’ will run the targets one, two, and three in parallel, while ‘make -j notparallel’ will run them serially.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you run ‘make -j all’ then they *will* be run in parallel since base lists them as prerequisites and is not serialized.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The `.NOTPARALLEL` target should not have commands.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Finally you can control the serialization of specific prerequisites in a fine-grained way using the `.WAIT` special target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] When this target appears in a prerequisite list and parallel execution is enabled, `make` will not build any of the prerequisites to the *right* of `.WAIT` until all prerequisites to the *left* of `.WAIT` have completed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If parallel execution is enabled, `make` will try to build one and two in parallel but will not try to build three until both are complete.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] As with targets provided to `.NOTPARALLEL`, `.WAIT` takes effect only when building the target in whose prerequisite list it appears.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the same prerequisites are present in other targets, without `.WAIT`, then they may still be run in parallel.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Because of this, neither `.NOTPARALLEL` with targets nor `.WAIT` are as reliable for controlling parallel execution as defining a prerequisite relationship.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However they are easy to use and may be sufficient in less complex situations.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The `.WAIT` prerequisite will not be present in any of the automatic variables for the rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] You can create an actual target `.WAIT` in your makefile for portability but this is not required to use this feature.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If a `.WAIT` target is created it should not have prerequisites or commands.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The `.WAIT` feature is also implemented in other versions of `make` and it’s specified in the POSIX standard for `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] When running several recipes in parallel the output from each recipe appears as soon as it is generated, with the result that messages from different recipes may be interspersed, sometimes even appearing on the same line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This can make reading the output very difficult.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] To avoid this you can use the ‘--output-sync’ (‘-O’) option.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This option instructs `make` to save the output from the commands it invokes and print it all once the commands are completed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Additionally, if there are multiple recursive `make` invocations running in parallel, they will communicate so that only one of them is generating output at a time.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If working directory printing is enabled (see The ‘--print-directory’ Option), the enter/leave messages are printed around each output grouping.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you prefer not to see these messages add the ‘--no-print-directory’ option to `MAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] There are four levels of granularity when synchronizing output, specified by giving an argument to the option (e.g., ‘-Oline’ or ‘--output-sync=recurse’).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is the default: all output is sent directly as it is generated and no synchronization is performed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Output from each individual line of the recipe is grouped and printed as soon as that line is complete.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If a recipe consists of multiple lines, they may be interspersed with lines from other recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Output from the entire recipe for each target is grouped and printed once the target is complete.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This is the default if the `--output-sync` or `-O` option is given with no argument.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Output from each recursive invocation of `make` is grouped and printed once the recursive invocation is complete.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Regardless of the mode chosen, the total build time will be the same.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The only difference is in how the output appears.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘target’ and ‘recurse’ modes both collect the output of the entire recipe of a target and display it uninterrupted when the recipe completes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The difference between them is in how recipes that contain recursive invocations of `make` are treated (see Recursive Use of `make`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] For all recipes which have no recursive lines, the ‘target’ and ‘recurse’ modes behave identically.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If the ‘recurse’ mode is chosen, recipes that contain recursive `make` invocations are treated the same as other targets: the output from the recipe, including the output from the recursive `make`, is saved and printed after the entire recipe is complete.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] This ensures output from all the targets built by a given recursive `make` instance are grouped together, which may make the output easier to understand.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] However it also leads to long periods of time during the build where no output is seen, followed by large bursts of output.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you are not watching the build as it proceeds, but instead viewing a log of the build after the fact, this may be the best option for you.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If you are watching the output, the long gaps of quiet during the build can be frustrating.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘target’ output synchronization mode detects when `make` is going to be invoked recursively, using the standard methods, and it will not synchronize the output of those lines.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The recursive `make` will perform the synchronization for its targets and the output from each will be displayed immediately when it completes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Be aware that output from recursive lines of the recipe are not synchronized (for example if the recursive line prints a message before running `make`, that message will not be synchronized).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] The ‘line’ mode can be useful for front-ends that are watching the output of `make` to track when recipes are started and completed.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] Some programs invoked by `make` may behave differently if they determine they’re writing output to a terminal versus a file (often described as “interactive” vs. “non-interactive” modes).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] For example, many programs that can display colorized output will not do so if they determine they are not writing to a terminal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p05] If your makefile invokes a program like this then using the output synchronization options will cause the program to believe it’s running in “non-interactive” mode even though the output will ultimately go to the terminal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Two processes cannot both take input from the same device at the same time.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] To make sure that only one recipe tries to take input from the terminal at once, `make` will invalidate the standard input streams of all but one running recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If another recipe attempts to read from standard input it will usually incur a fatal error (a ‘Broken pipe’ signal).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] It is unpredictable which recipe will have a valid standard input stream (which will come from the terminal, or wherever you redirect the standard input of `make`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The first recipe run will always get it first, and the first recipe started after that one finishes will get it next, and so on.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] We will change how this aspect of `make` works if we find a better alternative.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] In the mean time, you should not rely on any recipe using standard input at all if you are using the parallel execution feature; but if you are not using this feature, then standard input works normally in all recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] After each shell invocation returns, `make` looks at its exit status.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If the shell completed successfully (the exit status is zero), the next line in the recipe is executed in a new shell; after the last line is finished, the rule is finished.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If there is an error (the exit status is nonzero), `make` gives up on the current rule, and perhaps on all rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Sometimes the failure of a certain recipe line does not indicate a problem.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For example, you may use the `mkdir` command to ensure that a directory exists.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If the directory already exists, `mkdir` will report an error, but you probably want `make` to continue regardless.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] To ignore errors in a recipe line, write a ‘-’ at the beginning of the line’s text (after the initial tab).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The ‘-’ is discarded before the line is passed to the shell for execution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This causes `make` to continue even if `rm` is unable to remove a file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When you run `make` with the ‘-i’ or ‘--ignore-errors’ flag, errors are ignored in all recipes of all rules.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] A rule in the makefile for the special target `.IGNORE` has the same effect, if there are no prerequisites.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This is less flexible but sometimes useful.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When errors are to be ignored, because of either a ‘-’ or the ‘-i’ flag, `make` treats an error return just like success, except that it prints out a message that tells you the status code the shell exited with, and says that the error has been ignored.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When an error happens that `make` has not been told to ignore, it implies that the current target cannot be correctly remade, and neither can any other that depends on it either directly or indirectly.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] No further recipes will be executed for these targets, since their preconditions have not been achieved.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Normally `make` gives up immediately in this circumstance, returning a nonzero status.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] However, if the ‘-k’ or ‘--keep-going’ flag is specified, `make` continues to consider the other prerequisites of the pending targets, remaking them if necessary, before it gives up and returns nonzero status.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For example, after an error in compiling one object file, ‘make -k’ will continue compiling other object files even though it already knows that linking them will be impossible.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The usual behavior assumes that your purpose is to get the specified targets up to date; once `make` learns that this is impossible, it might as well report the failure immediately.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The ‘-k’ option says that the real purpose is to test as many of the changes made in the program as possible, perhaps to find several independent problems so that you can correct them all before the next attempt to compile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This is why Emacs’ `compile` command passes the ‘-k’ flag by default.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Usually when a recipe line fails, if it has changed the target file at all, the file is corrupted and cannot be used—or at least it is not completely updated.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Yet the file’s time stamp says that it is now up to date, so the next time `make` runs, it will not try to update that file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The situation is just the same as when the shell is killed by a signal; see Interrupting or Killing `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] So generally the right thing to do is to delete the target file if the recipe fails after beginning to change the file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] `make` will do this if `.DELETE_ON_ERROR` appears as a target.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This is almost always what you want `make` to do, but it is not historical practice; so for compatibility, you must explicitly request it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If `make` gets a fatal signal while a shell is executing, it may delete the target file that the recipe was supposed to update.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This is done if the target file’s last-modification time has changed since `make` first checked it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The purpose of deleting the target is to make sure that it is remade from scratch when `make` is next run.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Suppose you type Ctrl-c while a compiler is running, and it has begun to write an object file foo.o.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The Ctrl-c kills the compiler, resulting in an incomplete file whose last-modification time is newer than the source file foo.c.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] But `make` also receives the Ctrl-c signal and deletes this incomplete file.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If `make` did not do this, the next invocation of `make` would think that foo.o did not require updating—resulting in a strange error message from the linker when it tries to link an object file half of which is missing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can prevent the deletion of a target file in this way by making the special target `.PRECIOUS` depend on it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Before remaking a target, `make` checks to see whether it appears on the prerequisites of `.PRECIOUS`, and thereby decides whether the target should be deleted if a signal happens.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Some reasons why you might do this are that the target is updated in some atomic fashion, or exists only to record a modification-time (its contents do not matter), or must exist at all times to prevent other sorts of trouble.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Although `make` does its best to clean up there are certain situations in which cleanup is impossible.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For example, `make` may be killed by an uncatchable signal.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Or, one of the programs make invokes may be killed or crash, leaving behind an up-to-date but corrupt target file: `make` will not realize that this failure requires the target to be cleaned.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Or `make` itself may encounter a bug and crash.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For these reasons it’s best to write *defensive recipes*, which won’t leave behind corrupted targets even if they fail.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Most commonly these recipes create temporary files rather than updating the target directly, then rename the temporary file to the final target name.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Some compilers already behave this way, so that you don’t need to write a defensive recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Recursive use of `make` means using `make` as a command in a makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This technique is useful when you want separate makefiles for various subsystems that compose a larger system.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For example, suppose you have a sub-directory subdir which has its own makefile, and you would like the containing directory’s makefile to run `make` on the sub-directory.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can write recursive `make` commands just by copying this example, but there are many things to know about how they work and why, and about how the sub-`make` relates to the top-level `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You may also find it useful to declare targets that invoke recursive `make` commands as ‘.PHONY’ (for more discussion on when this is useful, see Phony Targets).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For your convenience, when GNU `make` starts (after it has processed any `-C` options) it sets the variable `CURDIR` to the pathname of the current working directory.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This value is never touched by `make` again: in particular note that if you include files from other directories the value of `CURDIR` does not change.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The value has the same precedence it would have if it were set in the makefile (by default, an environment variable `CURDIR` will not override this value).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Note that setting this variable has no impact on the operation of `make` (it does not cause `make` to change its working directory, for example).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The value of this variable is the file name with which `make` was invoked.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If this file name was /bin/make, then the recipe executed is ‘cd subdir && /bin/make’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you use a special version of `make` to run the top-level makefile, the same special version will be executed for recursive invocations.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] As a special feature, using the variable `MAKE` in the recipe of a rule alters the effects of the ‘-t’ (‘--touch’), ‘-n’ (‘--just-print’), or ‘-q’ (‘--question’) option.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Using the `MAKE` variable has the same effect as using a ‘+’ character at the beginning of the recipe line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This special feature is only enabled if the `MAKE` variable appears directly in the recipe: it does not apply if the `MAKE` variable is referenced through expansion of another variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] In the latter case you must use the ‘+’ token to get these special effects.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Consider the command ‘make -t’ in the above example.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] (The ‘-t’ option marks targets as up to date without actually running any recipes; see Instead of Executing Recipes.) Following the usual definition of ‘-t’, a ‘make -t’ command in the example would create a file named subsystem and do nothing else.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] What you really want it to do is run ‘cd subdir && make -t’; but that would require executing the recipe, and ‘-t’ says not to execute recipes.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The special feature makes this do what you want: whenever a recipe line of a rule contains the variable `MAKE`, the flags ‘-t’, ‘-n’ and ‘-q’ do not apply to that line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Recipe lines containing `MAKE` are executed normally despite the presence of a flag that causes most recipes not to be run.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The usual `MAKEFLAGS` mechanism passes the flags to the sub-`make` (see Communicating Options to a Sub-`make`), so your request to touch the files, or print the recipes, is propagated to the subsystem.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Variable values of the top-level `make` can be passed to the sub-`make` through the environment by explicit request.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] These variables are defined in the sub-`make` as defaults, but they do not override variables defined in the makefile used by the sub-`make` unless you use the ‘-e’ switch (see Summary of Options).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] To pass down, or *export*, a variable, `make` adds the variable and its value to the environment for running each line of the recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The sub-`make`, in turn, uses the environment to initialize its table of variable values.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Except by explicit request, `make` exports a variable only if it is either defined in the environment initially, or if set on the command line and its name consists only of letters, numbers, and underscores.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The value of the `make` variable `SHELL` is not exported.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Instead, the value of the `SHELL` variable from the invoking environment is passed to the sub-`make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can force `make` to export its value for `SHELL` by using the `export` directive, described below.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The special variable `MAKEFLAGS` is always exported (unless you unexport it).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] `MAKEFILES` is exported if you set it to anything.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] `make` automatically passes down variable values that were defined on the command line, by putting them in the `MAKEFLAGS` variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] See Communicating Options to a Sub-`make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Variables are *not* normally passed down if they were created by default by `make` (see Variables Used by Implicit Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The sub-`make` will define these for itself.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] In both of these forms, the arguments to `export` and `unexport` are expanded, and so could be variables or functions which expand to a (list of) variable names to be (un)exported.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You may notice that the `export` and `unexport` directives work in `make` in the same way they work in the shell, `sh`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This tells `make` that variables which are not explicitly mentioned in an `export` or `unexport` directive should be exported.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Any variable given in an `unexport` directive will still *not* be exported.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The behavior elicited by an `export` directive by itself was the default in older versions of GNU `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If your makefiles depend on this behavior and you want to be compatible with old versions of `make`, you can add the special target `.EXPORT_ALL_VARIABLES` to your makefile instead of using the `export` directive.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This will be ignored by old `make`s, while the `export` directive will cause a syntax error.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When using `export` by itself or `.EXPORT_ALL_VARIABLES` to export variables by default, only variables whose names consist solely of alphanumerics and underscores will be exported.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] To export other variables you must specifically mention them in an `export` directive.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Adding a variable’s value to the environment requires it to be expanded.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If expanding a variable has side-effects (such as the `info` or `eval` or similar functions) then these side-effects will be seen every time a command is invoked.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can avoid this by ensuring that such variables have names which are not exportable by default.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] However, a better solution is to *not* use this “export by default” facility at all, and instead explicitly `export` the relevant variables by name.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can use `unexport` by itself to tell `make` *not* to export variables by default.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Since this is the default behavior, you would only need to do this if `export` had been used by itself earlier (in an included makefile, perhaps).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You **cannot** use `export` and `unexport` by themselves to have variables exported for some recipes and not for others.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The last `export` or `unexport` directive that appears by itself determines the behavior for the entire run of `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] As a special feature, the variable `MAKELEVEL` is changed when it is passed down from level to level.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This variable’s value is a string which is the depth of the level as a decimal number.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The value is ‘0’ for the top-level `make`; ‘1’ for a sub-`make`, ‘2’ for a sub-sub-`make`, and so on.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The incrementation happens when `make` sets up the environment for a recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The main use of `MAKELEVEL` is to test it in a conditional directive (see Conditional Parts of Makefiles); this way you can write a makefile that behaves one way if run recursively and another way if run directly by you.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can use the variable `MAKEFILES` to cause all sub-`make` commands to use additional makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The value of `MAKEFILES` is a whitespace-separated list of file names.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This variable, if defined in the outer-level makefile, is passed down through the environment; then it serves as a list of extra makefiles for the sub-`make` to read before the usual or specified ones.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Flags such as ‘-s’ and ‘-k’ are passed automatically to the sub-`make` through the variable `MAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This variable is set up automatically by `make` to contain the flag letters that `make` received.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Thus, if you do ‘make -ks’ then `MAKEFLAGS` gets the value ‘ks’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] As a consequence, every sub-`make` gets a value for `MAKEFLAGS` in its environment.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] In response, it takes the flags from that value and processes them as if they had been given as arguments.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This means that, unlike other environment variables, `MAKEFLAGS` specified in the environment take precedence over `MAKEFLAGS` specified in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The value of `MAKEFLAGS` is a possibly empty group of characters representing single-letter options that take no argument, followed by a space and any options that take arguments or which have long option names.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If an option has both single-letter and long options, the single-letter option is always preferred.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If there are no single-letter options on the command line, then the value of `MAKEFLAGS` starts with a space.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Likewise variables defined on the command line are passed to the sub-`make` through `MAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Words in the value of `MAKEFLAGS` that contain ‘=’, `make` treats as variable definitions just as if they appeared on the command line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The options ‘-C’, ‘-f’, ‘-o’, and ‘-W’ are not put into `MAKEFLAGS`; these options are not passed down.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The ‘-j’ option is a special case (see Parallel Execution).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you set it to some numeric value ‘N’ and your operating system supports it (most any UNIX system will; others typically won’t), the parent `make` and all the sub-`make`s will communicate to ensure that there are only ‘N’ jobs running at the same time between them all.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If your operating system doesn’t support the above communication, then no ‘-j’ is added to `MAKEFLAGS`, so that sub-`make`s run in non-parallel mode.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If the ‘-j’ option were passed down to sub-`make`s you would get many more jobs running in parallel than you asked for.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you give ‘-j’ with no numeric argument, meaning to run as many jobs as possible in parallel, this is passed down, since multiple infinities are no more than one.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The command line variable definitions really appear in the variable `MAKEOVERRIDES`, and `MAKEFLAGS` contains a reference to this variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] However, some systems have a small fixed limit on the size of the environment, and putting so much information into the value of `MAKEFLAGS` can exceed it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you see the error message ‘Arg list too long’, this may be the problem.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] (For strict compliance with POSIX.2, changing `MAKEOVERRIDES` does not affect `MAKEFLAGS` if the special target ‘.POSIX’ appears in the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] A similar variable `MFLAGS` exists also, for historical compatibility.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] but now `MAKEFLAGS` makes this usage redundant.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you want your makefiles to be compatible with old `make` programs, use this technique; it will work fine with more modern `make` versions too.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The `MAKEFLAGS` variable can also be useful if you want to have certain options, such as ‘-k’ (see Summary of Options), set each time you run `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You simply put a value for `MAKEFLAGS` in your environment.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can also set `MAKEFLAGS` in a makefile, to specify additional flags that should also be in effect for that makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] (Note that you cannot use `MFLAGS` this way.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When `make` interprets the value of `MAKEFLAGS` (either from the environment or from a makefile), it first prepends a hyphen if the value does not already begin with one.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Then it chops the value into words separated by blanks, and parses these words as if they were options given on the command line (except that ‘-C’, ‘-f’, ‘-h’, ‘-o’, ‘-W’, and their long-named versions are ignored; and there is no error for an invalid option).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you do put `MAKEFLAGS` in your environment, you should be sure not to include any options that will drastically affect the actions of `make` and undermine the purpose of makefiles and of `make` itself.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] For instance, the ‘-t’, ‘-n’, and ‘-q’ options, if put in one of these variables, could have disastrous consequences and would certainly have at least surprising and probably annoying effects.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you’d like to run other implementations of `make` in addition to GNU `make`, and hence do not want to add GNU `make`-specific flags to the `MAKEFLAGS` variable, you can add them to the `GNUMAKEFLAGS` variable instead.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This variable is parsed just before `MAKEFLAGS`, in the same way as `MAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When `make` constructs `MAKEFLAGS` to pass to a recursive `make` it will include all flags, even those taken from `GNUMAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] As a result, after parsing `GNUMAKEFLAGS` GNU `make` sets this variable to the empty string to avoid duplicating flags during recursion.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] It’s best to use `GNUMAKEFLAGS` only with flags which won’t materially change the behavior of your makefiles.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If your makefiles require GNU Make anyway then simply use `MAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Flags such as ‘--no-print-directory’ or ‘--output-sync’ may be appropriate for `GNUMAKEFLAGS`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] If you use several levels of recursive `make` invocations, the ‘-w’ or ‘--print-directory’ option can make the output a lot easier to understand by showing each directory as `make` starts processing it and as `make` finishes processing it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Normally, you do not need to specify this option because ‘make’ does it for you: ‘-w’ is turned on automatically when you use the ‘-C’ option, and in sub-`make`s.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] `make` will not automatically turn on ‘-w’ if you also use ‘-s’, which says to be silent, or if you use ‘--no-print-directory’ to explicitly disable it.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] When the same sequence of commands is useful in making various targets, you can define it as a canned sequence with the `define` directive, and refer to the canned sequence from the recipes for those targets.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The canned sequence is actually a variable, so the name must not conflict with other variable names.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Here `run-yacc` is the name of the variable being defined; `endef` marks the end of the definition; the lines in between are the commands.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The `define` directive does not expand variable references and function calls in the canned sequence; the ‘$’ characters, parentheses, variable names, and so on, all become part of the value of the variable you are defining.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] See Defining Multi-Line Variables, for a complete explanation of `define`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The first command in this example runs Yacc on the first prerequisite of whichever rule uses the canned sequence.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The output file from Yacc is always named y.tab.c.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] The second command moves the output to the rule’s target file name.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] To use the canned sequence, substitute the variable into the recipe of a rule.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can substitute it like any other variable (see Basics of Variable References).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Because variables defined by `define` are recursively expanded variables, all the variable references you wrote inside the `define` are expanded now.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] ‘foo.y’ will be substituted for the variable ‘$^’ when it occurs in `run-yacc`’s value, and ‘foo.c’ for ‘$@’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This is a realistic example, but this particular one is not needed in practice because `make` has an implicit rule to figure out these commands based on the file names involved (see Using Implicit Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] In recipe execution, each line of a canned sequence is treated just as if the line appeared on its own in the rule, preceded by a tab.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] In particular, `make` invokes a separate sub-shell for each line.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You can use the special prefix characters that affect command lines (‘@’, ‘-’, and ‘+’) on each line of a canned sequence.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] `make` will not echo the first line, the `echo` command.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] But it *will* echo the following two recipe lines.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] On the other hand, prefix characters on the recipe line that refers to a canned sequence apply to every line in the sequence.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] It is sometimes useful to define recipes which do nothing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] This is done simply by giving a recipe that consists of nothing but whitespace.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You could also use a line beginning with a recipe prefix character to define an empty recipe, but this would be confusing because such a line looks empty.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You may be wondering why you would want to define a recipe that does nothing.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] One reason this is useful is to prevent a target from getting implicit recipes (from implicit rules or the `.DEFAULT` special target; see Using Implicit Rules and see Defining Last-Resort Default Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] Empty recipes can also be used to avoid errors for targets that will be created as a side-effect of another recipe: if the target does not exist the empty recipe ensures that `make` won’t complain that it doesn’t know how to build the target, and `make` will assume the target is out of date.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] You may be inclined to define empty recipes for targets that are not actual files, but only exist so that their prerequisites can be remade.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] However, this is not the best way to do that, because the prerequisites may not be remade properly if the target file actually does exist.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p06] See Phony Targets, for a better way to do this.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A *variable* is a name defined in a makefile to represent a string of text, called the variable’s *value*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] These values are substituted by explicit request into targets, prerequisites, recipes, and other parts of the makefile.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables and functions in all parts of a makefile are expanded when read, except for in recipes, the right-hand sides of variable definitions using ‘=’, and the bodies of variable definitions using the `define` directive.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The value a variable expands to is that of its most recent definition at the time of expansion.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] In other words, variables are dynamically scoped.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables can represent lists of file names, options to pass to compilers, programs to run, directories to look in for source files, directories to write output in, or anything else you can imagine.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A variable name may be any sequence of characters not containing ‘:’, ‘#’, ‘=’, or whitespace.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] However, variable names containing characters other than letters, numbers, and underscores should be considered carefully, as in some shells they cannot be passed through the environment to a sub-`make` (see Communicating Variables to a Sub-`make`).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variable names beginning with ‘.’ and an uppercase letter may be given special meaning in future versions of `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The names ‘foo’, ‘FOO’, and ‘Foo’ all refer to different variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A few variables have names that are a single punctuation character or just a few characters.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] These are the *automatic variables*, and they have particular specialized uses.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] To substitute a variable’s value, write a dollar sign followed by the name of the variable in parentheses or braces: either ‘$(foo)’ or ‘${foo}’ is a valid reference to the variable `foo`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This special significance of ‘$’ is why you must write ‘$$’ to have the effect of a single dollar sign in a file name or recipe.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variable references can be used in any context: targets, prerequisites, recipes, most directives, and new variable values.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variable references work by strict textual substitution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] could be used to compile a C program prog.c.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Since spaces before the variable value are ignored in variable assignments, the value of `foo` is precisely ‘c’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A dollar sign followed by a character other than a dollar sign, open-parenthesis or open-brace treats that single character as the variable name.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Thus, you could reference the variable `x` with ‘$x’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] However, this practice can lead to confusion (e.g., ‘$foo’ refers to the variable `f` followed by the string `oo`) so we recommend using parentheses or braces around all variables, even single-letter variables, unless omitting them gives significant readability improvements.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] One place where readability is often improved is automatic variables (see Automatic Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] There are different ways that a variable in GNU `make` can get a value; we call them the *flavors* of variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The flavors are distinguished in how they handle the values they are assigned in the makefile, and in how those values are managed when the variable is later used and expanded.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The first flavor of variable is a *recursively expanded* variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables of this sort are defined by lines using ‘=’ (see Setting Variables) or by the `define` directive (see Defining Multi-Line Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The value you specify is installed verbatim; if it contains references to other variables, these references are expanded whenever this variable is substituted (in the course of expanding some other string).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] When this happens, it is called *recursive expansion*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] will echo ‘Huh?’: ‘$(foo)’ expands to ‘$(bar)’ which expands to ‘$(ugh)’ which finally expands to ‘Huh?’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This flavor of variable is the only sort supported by most other versions of `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] It has its advantages and its disadvantages.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] will do what was intended: when ‘CFLAGS’ is expanded in a recipe, it will expand to ‘-Ifoo -Ibar -O’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] because it will cause an infinite loop in the variable expansion.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Another disadvantage is that any functions (see Functions for Transforming Text) referenced in the definition will be executed every time the variable is expanded.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This makes `make` run slower; worse, it causes the `wildcard` and `shell` functions to give unpredictable results because you cannot easily control when they are called, or even how many times.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] To avoid the problems and inconveniences of recursively expanded variables, there is another flavor: simply expanded variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The value of a simply expanded variable is scanned once, expanding any references to other variables and functions, when the variable is defined.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Once that expansion is complete the value of the variable is never expanded again: when the variable is used the value is copied verbatim as the expansion.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] If the value contained variable references the result of the expansion will contain their values *as of the time this variable was defined*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Here is a somewhat more complicated example, illustrating the use of ‘:=’ in conjunction with the `shell` function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] (See The `shell` Function.) This example also shows use of the variable `MAKELEVEL`, which is changed when it is passed down from level to level.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Simply expanded variables generally make complicated makefile programming more predictable because they work like variables in most programming languages.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] They allow you to redefine a variable using its own value (or its value processed in some way by one of the expansion functions) and to use the expansion functions much more efficiently (see Functions for Transforming Text).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] You can also use them to introduce controlled leading whitespace into variable values.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Here the value of the variable `space` is precisely one space.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The comment ‘# end of the line’ is included here just for clarity.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Since trailing space characters are *not* stripped from variable values, just a space at the end of the line would have the same effect (but be rather hard to read).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] If you put whitespace at the end of a variable value, it is a good idea to put a comment like that at the end of the line to make your intent clear.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Here the value of the variable `dir` is ‘/foo/bar ’ (with four trailing spaces), which was probably not the intention.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Another form of assignment allows for immediate expansion, but unlike simple assignment the resulting variable is recursive: it will be re-expanded again on every use.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] In order to avoid unexpected results, after the value is immediately expanded it will automatically be quoted: all instances of `$` in the value after expansion will be converted into `$$`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This type of assignment uses the ‘:::=’ operator.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] results in the `OUT` variable containing the text ‘one$$two’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The value is expanded when the variable is assigned, so the result is the expansion of the first value of `var`, ‘one$two’; then the value is re-escaped before the assignment is complete giving the final result of ‘one$$two’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The variable `OUT` is thereafter considered a recursive variable, so it will be re-expanded when it is used.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] First, after assignment the variable is a normal recursive variable; when you append to it with ‘+=’ the value on the right-hand side is not expanded immediately.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] If you prefer the ‘+=’ operator to expand the right-hand side immediately you should use the ‘:=’ / ‘::=’ assignment instead.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Second, these variables are slightly less efficient than simply expanded variables since they do need to be re-expanded when they are used, rather than merely copied.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] However since all variable references are escaped this expansion simply un-escapes the value, it won’t expand any variables or run any functions.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] After this, the value of `OUT` is the text ‘one$$two $(var)’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] When this variable is used it will be expanded and the result will be ‘one$two three$four’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This style of assignment is equivalent to the traditional BSD `make` ‘:=’ operator; as you can see it works slightly differently than the GNU `make` ‘:=’ operator.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The `:::=` operator is added to the POSIX specification in Issue 8 to provide portability.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] There is another assignment operator for variables, ‘?=’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This is called a conditional variable assignment operator, because it only has an effect if the variable is not yet defined.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Note that a variable set to an empty value is still defined, so ‘?=’ will not set that variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This section describes some advanced features you can use to reference variables in more flexible ways.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A *substitution reference* substitutes the value of a variable with alterations that you specify.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] It has the form ‘$(*var*:*a*=*b*)’ (or ‘${*var*:*a*=*b*}’) and its meaning is to take the value of the variable *var*, replace every *a* at the end of a word with *b* in that value, and substitute the resulting string.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] When we say “at the end of a word”, we mean that *a* must appear either followed by whitespace or at the end of the value in order to be replaced; other occurrences of *a* in the value are unaltered.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A substitution reference is shorthand for the `patsubst` expansion function (see Functions for String Substitution and Analysis): ‘$(*var*:*a*=*b*)’ is equivalent to ‘$(patsubst %*a*,%*b*,*var*)’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] We provide substitution references as well as `patsubst` for compatibility with other implementations of `make`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Another type of substitution reference lets you use the full power of the `patsubst` function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] It has the same form ‘$(*var*:*a*=*b*)’ described above, except that now *a* must contain a single ‘%’ character.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] See Functions for String Substitution and Analysis, for a description of the `patsubst` function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Computed variable names are an advanced concept, very useful in more sophisticated makefile programming.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] In simple situations you need not consider them, but they can be extremely useful.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables may be referenced inside the name of a variable.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This is called a *computed variable name* or a *nested variable reference*.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Here the name of the variable to reference is not stated explicitly; it is computed by expansion of ‘$(x)’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The reference ‘$(x)’ here is nested within the outer variable reference.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The previous example shows two levels of nesting, but any number of levels is possible.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Here the innermost ‘$(x)’ expands to ‘y’, so ‘$($(x))’ expands to ‘$(y)’ which in turn expands to ‘z’; now we have ‘$(z)’, which becomes ‘u’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] References to recursively-expanded variables within a variable name are re-expanded in the usual fashion.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Nested variable references can also contain modified references and function invocations (see Functions for Transforming Text), just like any other reference.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] It is doubtful that anyone would ever want to write a nested reference as convoluted as this one, but it works: ‘$($($(z)))’ expands to ‘$($(y))’ which becomes ‘$($(subst 1,2,$(x)))’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This gets the value ‘variable1’ from `x` and changes it by substitution to ‘variable2’, so that the entire string becomes ‘$(variable2)’, a simple variable reference whose value is ‘Hello’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] A computed variable name need not consist entirely of a single variable reference.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] It can contain several variable references, as well as some invariant text.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] will give `dirs` the same value as `a_dirs`, `1_dirs`, `a_files` or `1_files` depending on the settings of `use_a` and `use_dirs`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] defines `sources` as either ‘a.c b.c c.c’ or ‘1.c 2.c 3.c’, depending on the value of `a1`.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The only restriction on this sort of use of nested variable references is that they cannot specify part of the name of a function to be called.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This is because the test for a recognized function name is done before the expansion of nested references.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] attempts to give ‘foo’ the value of the variable ‘sort a d b g q c’ or ‘strip a d b g q c’, rather than giving ‘a d b g q c’ as the argument to either the `sort` or the `strip` function.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This restriction could be removed in the future if that change is shown to be a good idea.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This example defines the variables ‘dir’, ‘foo_sources’, and ‘foo_print’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Note that *nested variable references* are quite different from *recursively expanded variables* (see The Two Flavors of Variables), though both are used together in complex ways when doing makefile programming.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] To set a variable from the makefile, write a line starting with the variable name followed by one of the assignment operators ‘=’, ‘:=’, ‘::=’, or ‘:::=’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Whatever follows the operator and any initial whitespace on the line becomes the value.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] defines a variable named `objects` to contain the value ‘main.o foo.o bar.o utils.o’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Whitespace around the variable name and immediately after the ‘=’ is ignored.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables defined with ‘=’ are *recursively expanded* variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables defined with ‘:=’ or ‘::=’ are *simply expanded* variables; these definitions can contain variable references which will be expanded before the definition is made.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Variables defined with ‘:::=’ are *immediately expanded* variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The different assignment operators are described in See The Two Flavors of Variables.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The variable name may contain function and variable references, which are expanded when the line is read to find the actual variable name to use.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] There is no limit on the length of the value of a variable except the amount of memory on the computer.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] You can split the value of a variable into multiple physical lines for readability (see Splitting Long Lines).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Most variable names are considered to have the empty string as a value if you have never set them.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Several variables have built-in initial values that are not empty, but you can set them in the usual ways (see Variables Used by Implicit Rules).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] Several special variables are set automatically to a new value for each rule; these are called the *automatic* variables (see Automatic Variables).
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] If you’d like a variable to be set to a value only if it’s not already set, then you can use the shorthand operator ‘?=’ instead of ‘=’.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] The shell assignment operator ‘!=’ can be used to execute a shell script and set a variable to its output.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] This operator first evaluates the right-hand side, then passes that result to the shell for execution.
[src:build-systems/manual-make-p07] If the result of the execution ends in a newline, that one newline is removed; all other newlines are replaced by spaces.
